<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Foreign Minister Backs Poland's Quick Entrance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 30 (Xinhua)-Berlin supports Poland to get the
European Union (EU) membership "as quickly as possible", said
German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer Monday at the annual
meeting with his Polish and French counterpart, Bronislaw Geremek
and Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
"Ten years after the end of Cold War there is the question,
when the EU can also overstep the former border between the two
blocks," Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
"In my personal view, Poland is already a EU member," he added,
underlining the fact that Poland had been accepted as a NATO
member and its economy had been closely integrated with Germany
and the EU.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, also known as "Weimar Triangle", is an initiative
raised by then German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher in
1991. Since that year, ministers of Germany, France and Poland
have held talks every year in one of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pleased and satisfied that Poland, Germany and France are
working together for the building-up of Europe, on the eve of the
60th anniversary of German intrusion in Poland," said Fischer,
recalling that Nazi Germany attacked Poland and triggered World
War II on September 1, 1939.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in Weimar, the "European Cultural Capital" known
for German poet and writer Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, was also
focused on cultural issues. This year is the 250th anniversary of
Goethe's birth.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine suggested that, the "triangle meeting" should be
extended into cultural fields in the future, and cultural
institutes of the three countries should better coordinate with
each other.
</P>
<P>
"Europe is a cultural unity," said Geremek. The Polish minister
stressed the Slavic culture, to which belongs the Polish culture,
was "a part of European cultural heritage."
</P>
<P>
Further, they discussed the situation in Kosovo, and reaffirmed
their top goal of building a "multi-ethnic and pluralistic"
society in the war-torn region, according to Fischer.
</P>
<P>
Political aides of the three ministers are drafting a common
bulletin on these issues, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
