<HEADLINE> Canada Reports Travel Deficit Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Statistics reported
Monday an increase of 392 million Canadian dollars (about 263
million U.S. dollars) in travel deficit for the second quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Canadians spent 4.1 billion Canadian dollars (about 2.8 billion
U.S. dollars) travelling abroad between April and June, a rise of
0.1 percent from the first quarter, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
For the same period, foreigners spent 3.7 billion Canadian
dollars (about 2.5 billion U.S. dollars) in the country, a drop of
5.7 percent from the first three months, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
The second quarter travel deficit is largely attributed to
Americans, whose spending in Canada dropped 3.3 percent to almost
2.4 billion Canadian dollars (about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
That alone left a deficit of 216 million Canadian dollars
(about 145 million U.S. dollars), as Canadians spent nearly 2.6
billion dollars of their own (about 1.7 billion U.S. dollars) in
the U.S..
</P>
<P>
More Canadians were reported to go south of the border for fun
and shopping from April to June, as a result of a three percent
increase in the exchange rate of the Canadian dollar against the
U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
