<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- The first batch of China's aid materials for the
Turkish earthquake victims arrived at the Ataturk Airport in
Istanbul early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The aid materials including 526 tents will be sent to the
disaster region from the airport.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Red Cross has provided search and rescue materials
worth 60,000 U.S. dollars to Turkey. The Chinese government will
send a total of 100 tons of aid materials including tents,
blankets and medicines to the quake-devastated country.
(BC-Turkey-Quake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami has reportedly
asked a "top decision-making body" to send a strong reply to the
United States in response to its recent "veiled threat."
</P>
<P>
"Tehran Times" newspaper on Monday quoted an informed source
as saying the "veiled threat" was contained in a letter the
U.S. sent via Oman, which has cordial relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear if the letter was concerning Iran's
territorial dispute with the United Arab Emirates over three
islands at the mouth of strategically important Strait of
Hormuz. (BC-Iran-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's national soccer team has been invited by the
United States Soccer Federation to play three friendly matches in
the U.S. at the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
The official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported that
the invitation has been forwarded to the Iranian Soccer Federation.
</P>
<P>
The three matches are Iran vs El-Salvador on January 9, 2000 in
Los Angeles; Iran vs Mexican national team on January 12, in San
Francisco; and Iran vs the U.S. in Los Angles on January 16.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said the Iranian Soccer Federation has not yet responded
to the invitation. (BC-Iran-US-Soccer)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak abandoned an
ultimatum to the Palestinians Monday, saying he expected answers
from Palestinian leaders within three days to his proposed
modification of a U.S.-brokered peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a parliamentary committee of foreign and defense
affairs, Barak said it would be known within three days whether
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat would agree
to Israeli proposals on the implementation of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
Barak told reporters after the briefing that if Arafat rejects
the modification to the agreement, Israel would carry it out "by
the book," or according to Israeli interpretation, which analysts
said would harm further Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
(BC-Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The Iraqi Red Crescent Society has formed a
delegation to visit Turkey to distribute 10 million U.S. dollars
worth of oil as assistance to the quake-hit country, an Iraqi
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
President of the society Sadiq Hameed Aloosh told a press
conference that Iraq offered its oil as assistance because it has
no hard currency due to nine years of United Nations embargo,
imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Aloosh did not say when the delegation will leave for Turkey.
(BC-Iraqi Red Crescent-Turkey) 
</P>
</TEXT>
