<HEADLINE> Rwanda Pledges Commitment to Lusaka Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Vice-President Paul
Kagame Wednesday reiterated Rwanda's commitment to the Lusaka
accord, saying that his country would pull its troops out of the
Congo immediately, if any one take up the responsibility to grant
Rwanda security.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliamentarians, Kagame, also the defense
minister, said the recent battle between Rwandan and Uganda
forces in Kisangani was a ''shame'' of the two friendly countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Rwandan News Agency, Kagame refused to comment on
allegations that Rwanda was the aggressor and had the intention to
oust rebel leader Ernest Wamba dia Wamba and his faction.
</P>
<P>
Kagame said the relations between Rwanda and Uganda have not
been affected by the Kisangani incidents, adding that leaders of
both countries are trying to investigate the cause and put in
place mechanisms so that the tragedy would not reoccur. 
</P>
</TEXT>
