<HEADLINE> E-Commerce Threat to UK Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Internet shopping by Britons
could cost the Inland Revenue of the British Government up to 10
billion pounds (16 billion U.S. dollars) in lost taxes each year,
according to a report published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The taxman is already missing out on possible VAT payments from
the huge amounts of music and software bought and downloaded
electronically from suppliers based overseas, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Institute of Directors (IoD) says that as the
Internet encourages more people to buy goods from overseas, the
tax shortfall will spiral. The report follows a survey from the
NOP research group, which found that the UK is undergoing an
e-commerce explosion.
</P>
<P>
It found that almost 1.5 million people in the UK shopped on
the Internet in the four weeks to 1 June this year, spending 239
million pounds (382 million U.S. dollars). This was a 44 percent
increase on the numbers identified in a similar survey in
December.
</P>
<P>
And spending on online shopping in the UK will rise from about
3 billion pounds (4.8 billion U.S.dollars) this year to about 9.5
billion pounds (16 billion U.S. dollars) by the end of 2001, NOP
suggested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
