<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Starts Visit to Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 30 (Xinhua) - Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa arrived in Sweden Monday for a six-day official
visit to the Scandinavian country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a banquet hosted by Swedish Prime Minister Goran
Persson in Stockholm, Mkapa expressed hopes that the two countries
could strengthen ties on the basis of long period of co-operation
and friendship, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian President is accompanied by his wife Anna Mkapa,
Minister of Foreign Affairs and International Co-operation Jakaya
Kikwete, Minister of Industries and Commerce, Iddi Simba, as well
as other senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicated that Tanzania's imports from
Sweden grew from 10.5 billion shillings (about 13 million U.S.
dollars) in 1997 to 18.7 billion shillings (about 23 million
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
But Tanzania's exports to Sweden have been declining, reaching
about 900 million shillings (1.1 million dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Tanzania consisted of agricultural products, such
as coffee, tea, cocoa and spices. Dwindling export earnings of
agricultural products from Tanzania to Sweden are the result of
low export volumes caused by low production. Weather vagaries and
poor technology are the chief reason for this.
</P>
<P>
In the near future, there should be a potential for increased
revenues to Tanzania from Swedish tourists, according to a report
by the Dar es Salaam-based Business Times.
</P>
<P>
On investment and joint ventures, the report said that there
have already been quite a few investments and joint ventures
between Sweden and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
To promote joint ventures and direct investments on a more
partner-like basis, there are several instruments available
through the Swedish International Development Agency, and other
government or commercial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has been a major donor to Tanzania, providing assistance
to social and economic reforms as well as other sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
