<HEADLINE> Security Council Demands End to Violence against  Kosovar Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday demanded an immediate end to the violence against civilian
population in Kosovo, in particular against ethnic minorities in
the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
Security Council for the month of August, Martin Andjaba of
Namibia, said, the council members "condemned violence against the
civilian population, in particular against ethnic minorities, as
well as against KFOR personnel." KFOR stands for the international
peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"They demanded that such acts cease immediately," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council reaffirmed the principle of respect for
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the FRY (the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia)," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the 15-nation Security Council met in
a closed-door session to exchange views on the situation in
Kosovo, and the implementation of the Security Council Resolution
1244, adopted on June 10.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council reaffirmed the utmost importance of
full implementation of Security Council Resolution 1244 and
reiterated the need to comply fully with the demands of the
resolution and to cooperate fully with UNMIK (the U.N. Interim
Administration Mission in Kosovo) and KFOR to this end," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "called on Member States to provide UNMIK
with resources necessary to carry out its functions under Security
Council Resolution 1244," the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
