<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU: SMEs Can Play Role in Technology Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs) can play a significant role in bringing the
benefits of globalization to developing countries, especially in
the crucial area of technology transfer, a newly published study
said.
</P>
<P>
SMEs' flexibility allows them to adapt quickly to a volatile
market, and their diversity means they can exploit new niche
markets which larger firms would find uneconomical, said the
study, a working report for an expert panel of the European
Parliament, the supervisory and policy-making branch of the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The SMEs tend to be spread out more, which makes for more
balanced industrial development, and they have lower start-up
costs and can create jobs with a low capital investment, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The study, which assessed the range of EU programs trying to
support SMEs in the developing world and link them with their
counterparts EU-wide, said that "all these and other factors allow
SMEs to go with the flow of recent economic trends, such as the
move to a knowledge-based market, and the growing need to keep up
with rapid innovation".
</P>
<P>
Referring to how the factors have supported "the importance of
horizontal networking between businesses and other economic actors
- which, again, favors SMEs", the report said this has had a
particular impact on technology transfer, which takes place less
and less through traditional ways and more through a transient web
of strategic alliances or temporary agreements.
</P>
<P>
The tide, it said, is moving in the direction of smaller firms.
"There are still obstacles, however, and it is these obstacles
which the EU's various support programs need to overcome. Many of
them are the flip side of the very advantages SMEs have in the
global market place."
</P>
<P>
The size of SMEs makes them flexible, but it can also mean that
they lack a long-term strategy, or that they can't control or
transfer the technology they use. "They find it harder to get
credit, and so have a greater sense of risk - which can make them
vulnerable and cautious," they therefore need the right kind of
support, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The EU report pointed out that the key to boosting technology
transfer between the industrialized and developing worlds is not
necessarily to back individual SMEs, but to try and stimulate the
growth of the systems of relations from which they can draw
resources because "technology transfer doesn't mean passing
hardware or expertise down the line". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
