<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Deaths Down in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Deaths from AIDS declined 20
percent in the United States between 1997 and 1998 due to the
effectiveness of new drugs, U.S. health officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released at the national HIV
Prevention Conference in Atlanta Monday, AIDS killed 17,047 people
in the United States last year, down from 21,222 in 1997. From
1996 to 1997, the drop in deaths was a much more dramatic 42
percent.
</P>
<P>
"As we anticipated, we are now seeing the first signs of a
slowing in this trend," said Dr. Helene Gayle, director of HIV
prevention for the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDC).
</P>
<P>
"In a period of only two years, new combination therapies cut
the annual level of death in half," she said. "But for the time
being it appears that much of the benefit of these new therapies
has been realized."
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, more than 300,000 have died of AIDS in the
United States. In 1995, 49,351 people died from AIDS. By 1996,
that dropped to 36,792, and the number was down to 21,222 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
New HIV infections in 1998 were estimated at roughly 40,000
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Blacks, who make up about 13 percent of the population,
accounted for 49 percent of AIDS deaths in 1998 while 32 percent
of deaths were among whites and 18 percent among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, organized by the CDC and 17 other
agencies, features 2,000 scientists, doctors, researchers and
advocates addressing efforts to monitor and prevent the spread of
HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
