<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says East Timor's Referendum a "Success" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
called a referendum on the future of East Timor a success.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters that all
reports -- official and unofficial -- "indicate that the
U.N.-administered vote in East Timor was a success, with
approximately 90 percent of those registered casting ballots."
</P>
<P>
"This is really an extraordinary figure," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the next phases of the process -- counting the
vote and transition to either independence or autonomy within
Indonesia -- Foley said: "Indonesia maintains the responsibility
for maintaining order and we remain concerned about the potential
for violence."
</P>
<P>
"In particular the government of Indonesia should prevent armed
militia from resuming their activities," he added.
</P>
<P>
Foley also said according to U.N. accounts, a number of polling
stations were temporarily closed but that did not prevent any
individual from voting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
