<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Red Crescent Delegation to Visit Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi Red Crescent Society
has formed a delegation to visit Turkey to distribute 10 million
U.S. dollars worth of oil as assistance to the quake-hit country,
an Iraqi official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
President of the society Sadiq Hameed Aloosh told a press
conference that Iraq offered its oil as assistance because it has
no hard currency due to nine years of United Nations embargo,
imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Aloosh did not say when the delegation will leave for Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government on Sunday decided to offer 10 million
dollars worth of oil as assistance to families of victims of the
strong earthquake that recently hit Turkey.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake of 7.4 magnitude struck populous northwestern
Turkey on August 17, leaving some 14,000 people killed and 43,000
others injured so far. It was feared that the death toll would
break 40,000 as tens of thousands of people were still buried
under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Red Crescent Society will coordinate with its
Turkish counterpart to draw up the distribution plan of the
assistance, said Aloosh.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had started pumping oil to Turkey on Sunday, adding that
it will pump 500,000 barrels of oil to Turkey in five days, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
