<HEADLINE> Angolan Rebels Launch Fresh Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Angolan rebels launched another
round of attack at the weekend, killing four, injuring many and
destroying a bridge, local media reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the north province of Lunda-norte, close to the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC), rebels of the National Union for
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) ambushed civilian vehicles
in a stretch of road connecting the Fucauma village and the Zanji
Town, leaving four dead and another four severely injured.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses of the incident said that the action was launched
Saturday by well-equipped militants, in the uniform of DRC regular
forces, 90 kilometers east to Dundo, an important fortress held by
the government troops near the Angola-DRC border, said the news
agency Angop.
</P>
<P>
Military source in Dundo said that this is the fifth terrorist
act of its kind registered in the region in less than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
In the central-west Benguela province, a bridge over the Camoko
River, part of an important road linking the main cities of the
Lobito, Bocoio and Balombo provinces, was also destroyed by UNITA
rebels in this attack, said Angop.
</P>
<P>
According to a local government official, destroying
infrastructure is a habitual action of Jonas Savimbi, the UNITA
leader, for creating social crisis and forcing the government to
spend heavily on reconstructions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
