<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African FM to Witness Congolese Accord Signing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 30 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Nkosazana Zuma Monday left for Lusaka to witness
Tuesday's signing of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
cease-fire agreement by a major rebel group.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government hopes that the signing will take
place without any hitches, and that the implementation of the
peace process can start in earnest," South African Press
Association quoted Zuma as telling reporters in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said the signing should be followed within 24 hours by a
complete cease-fire. This would lead to the formation within seven
days of a joint military commission comprising all the warring
factions in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the commission would be an individual from
outside the countries involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The third step, Zuma said, would be the deployment of observers
from the United Nations and the Organization of African Unity
(OAU), probably also within a few days of the signing.
</P>
<P>
She said it could take months before peacekeeping troops are
sent to that country. The OAU and the United Nations would decide
which countries to invite to take part in the peacekeeping
exercise, and what kind of support they would be asked to render.
</P>
<P>
"Only then can we (South Africa) really say how our involvement
is going to be," Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said that Burundi would be involved in steps to secure a
cease-fire in the DRC, as it shared the security concerns of
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The major rebel group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD),
did not sign the July cease-fire agreement due to a squabble about
who would sign on its behalf.
</P>
<P>
Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, who was expelled from the rebel group
in May, has insisted on signing the document, while the current
leadership refused to sign if Wamba did.
</P>
<P>
It has since been agreed that all 51 founding members of the
rebel group would add their names to the peace accord, including
Wamba dia Wamba and current RCD leader Emile Ilunga.
</P>
<P>
The document has already been signed by DRC President Laurent
Kabila and his military allies Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, as
well as by Uganda and Rwanda -- who backed the rival rebel
factions in the year-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
Zuma would represent President Thabo Mbeki at the signing
ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
