<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Obtains Loan for Wildlife Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the signing ceremony in Harare, Zimbabwean Mines,
Environment and Tourism Minister Simon Moyo said the Zimbabwean
government regarded wildlife as a national heritage which must
provide benefits to the Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposals to establish involving co-management of
the resources within the conservancy, with the surrounding
communities is a move in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
The Save Valley has in the past lost wildlife as there was no
management to protect fauna and flora, he said.
</P>
<P>
The local communities and the Save Valley Conservancy formed a
trust to jointly run projects that involve the restocking of
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
The minister added in order to protect wildlife, at the
Southern African Development Community summit held recently in
Mozambique, leaders of the 14- member community signed a protocol
on wildlife conservation. 
