<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Pleased with East Timor Ballot Turnout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan expressed his satisfaction over the large turnout in
East Timor's ballot held as scheduled on Monday on its future
while calling for more security measures in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Despite sporadic incidents, Annan paid tribute to the efforts
of the Indonesian authorities and particularly of the police on
the polling day when well over 90 percent of all registered voters
cast their ballots, Annan's spokesman stated on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
Describing the polling as smooth, Annan congratulated Portugal
and Indonesia for their "spirit of cooperation and collegiality"
during the polling process.
</P>
<P>
The referendum under an agreement among Indonesia, Portugal and
the United Nations was for voters to choose between special
autonomy within Indonesia or independence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in
1976, has been seen by the United Nations General Assembly as a
non-self-governing territory.
</P>
<P>
The ballot, organized and conducted by the U.N. as ageed upon
by the parties, had been delayed twice because of violent
incidents by anti-independence and pro-independence activists in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. recruited worker was murdered on the voting day.
</P>
<P>
"The role of the security forces will be even more important in
the coming days as ballot boxes are transported to the central
counting station and the count begins," Annan said, calling on all
local groups to exercise the utmost restraint and patience.
</P>
<P>
The sealed ballot boxes will be transported to Dili, the
capital by mid-day Tuesday and the process of counting,
verification and certification is expected to take a week before
the vote is announced, said Manoel de Almeida e Silva, Deputy
Spokesman for the U.N. Secretary-General. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
