<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's High Court Tries Three Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The High Court in Harare Monday
continued with their case against three Americans arrested for
being found in possession of arms of war.
</P>
<P>
These Americans are Joseph Pettijohn, John Dixon and Garry
Blanchard.
</P>
<P>
Pettijohn told the High Court that he agreed with the evidence
given by Charles Haley, a technician from the Forensic Department
of Zimbabwe Republic Police, that the weapons could be used in
offensive situations.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, although the weapons could be used for
assassination purposes, they had never thought of using them that
way.
</P>
<P>
Under cross examination by Prosecutor Joseph Musakwa, Pettijohn
 maintained that they had kept the weapons for self defense and
hunting opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He said they did not declare the weapons both in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo and Zimbabwe because they feared
confiscation.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe alleges that Pettijohn, Dixon and Blanchard were found
in possession of arms of war on March 7, this year at the Harare
International Airport, which is against the Aircraft Act and the
Law and Order Maintenance Act.
</P>
<P>
The case would continue next Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
