<HEADLINE> Chinese Stamp Collectors Admire Penny Black (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 30 (Xinhua) -- For the second time in ten days,
32-year-old Yu Yang got the okay from his boss to leave work at a
Beijing computer firm and attend the World Philately Exhibition.
The object of his interest: the world's first official postal
stamp, the "Penny Black."
</P>
<P>
"My boss gave me a day off specially for the exhibition. He is
a stamp lover like me," said Yu. "Stamps such as the Penny Black
are in China for the first time, and the opportunity to see them
is too precious."
</P>
<P>
The ten-day event, which closed today at the Beijing
International Exhibition Center, attracted more than 300,000 stamp
collectors from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition to 3,322 sets of stamps from the world over, the
exhibition also offered rare stamps such as the Penny Black and
the Mauritius Post Office Stamp.
</P>
<P>
"The guards here are the most tired as 99 if not 100 percent of
visitors jostle to see Penny Black," said Shang Xiuwei, who
oversees security in the hall.
</P>
<P>
The Penny Black, issued by the United Kingdom in 1840, is the
envy of stamp collectors throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Only recently have Chinese stamp collectors paid attention to
foreign stamps, much less collected them.
</P>
<P>
"The trends are changing," said Xu Jihai, senior editor with
the People's Post and Telecommunications Publishing House, adding
that the change indicates the improvement of people's living
standards and the country's level of sophistication of stamp
collecting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Stamp Collectors Admire Penny Black (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"As more people know more about the world and have more money,
it's natural they will be interested in buying foreign stamps," Xu
said.
</P>
<P>
Xu earns several thousand yuan a month; an entire set of stamps
costs only several hundred yuan.
</P>
<P>
"I still remember when I was in school, my living expense for a
month was 20 yuan, but a set of stamps sometimes cost one half or
one third of that."
</P>
<P>
Crowds surrounded the stands where dealers from 67 countries
sold stamps and other mail-related items.
</P>
<P>
"If Black Penny were auctioned, many stamp collectors here would
have bought it," said a stamp buyer at the Russian stamp stand who
didn't give his name.
</P>
<P>
China currently has 20 million stamp collectors -- the largest
contingent of stamp collectors in the world. In 1998, the country'
s total revenue from philately reached 7.79 billion yuan,
accounting for 14 percent of the postal business volume.
</P>
<P>
"In China, stamp collecting only existed in the old days for
very few people," said Knud Mohr, President of the Federation of
International Philately. "Now, everybody is given the opportunity
to collect stamps. It's very impressive. "  
</P>
</TEXT>
