<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Professor: Smoking for 20 Years Causes Lung Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Smoking for 20 years are enough
to cause lung cancer, which is among the main causes of death in
the world, a Greek university professor said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kostas Zarogoulidis, professor for pulmonary disease at
Greece's Aristotle University, said at a press conference in the
northern Greek city of Thessaloniki that the risk of developing
lung cancer increases 7 times if a person smokes 13 cigarettes a
day, while 20 cigarettes a day make the risk 10 times higher, the
Macedonian Press Agency (MPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
There is a five percent likelihood for the disease to appear in
passive smokers, he added.
</P>
<P>
The professor said that in Europe, lung cancer appears in men
at a 6 to 1 ratio compared to women because women smoke less.
</P>
<P>
The lack of symptoms offering an early warning to the patients
is the main cause for the increased number of deaths by lung
cancer compared to other cancer types, he said, adding that in
Europe only 1 out 3 is diagnosed with the disease when it is at
its early stages, while in Greece the ratio is 1 out of 7.
</P>
<P>
However, he continued that even those who are diagnosed early
show a low survival rate because 80 percent of the lung cancer
types are very resistant to chemotherapy and 40 percent do not
respond to X-ray treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
