<HEADLINE> Leader of Congolese Rebel Backs Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Leader of a Congolese rebel
faction said his forces would stop fighting after the signing of
the ceasefire accord and begin talks to create a new political
order in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Emile Ilunga, leader of the main group of the now splintered
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) said here on Monday he
reluctantly backed the truce to be signed in the Zambian capital
Lusaka on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to sign the ceasefire tomorrow. We are signing
not as a matter of weakness but to give peace a chance in our
country and to allow for the creation of a new political order
through political dialog," Ilunga said.
</P>
<P>
But in Kigali, Lambert Mende, a spokesman for Ilunga's faction,
said the peace would be short-lived unless major democratic
reforms, including the removal of President Laurent Kabila from
power, were implemented.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's event will be overseen by regional foreign ministers,
the United Nations and Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, who
has acted as a mediator in the conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Six African countries directly involved in the conflict signed
a peace agreement on July 10 in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The rebel groups could not sign the pact because of internal
leadership wrangles in RCD while the other rebel group, the
Movement for the Liberation of the Congo (MLC) led by Pierre
Bemba, signed the agreement early this month.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Zambian Presidential Affairs Minister Eric Silwamba
said the arrival of the RCD leader was positive indication that
all the other stake- holders would be in Lusaka for the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba, who just returned from Rwanda, Uganda and Eastern
Congo (K) as Chiluba's special envoy where he had gone to verify
who led the trouble- torn RCD.
</P>
<P>
The stand-off in the rebel group was between Ilunga, supported
by Rwanda and Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, supported by Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba disclosed that all the 50 founding members of the RCD
would append their signatures to the ceasefire deal which is
expected to strengthen the fragile agreement sign by the six
regional states last month.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources close to the rebel told Xinhua by telephone,
Wamba dia Wamba has just arrived in Lusaka Monday afternoon for
the signing ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
