<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Abandons Ultimatum on Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak abandoned an ultimatum to the Palestinians Monday, saying he
expected answers from Palestinian leaders within three days to his
proposed modification of a U.S.-brokered peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a parliamentary committee of foreign and defense
affairs, Barak said it would be known within three days whether
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat would agree
to Israeli proposals on the implementation of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The prospects (for an agreement), I believe, are more than
50-50," Barak told reporters after the briefing.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that if Arafat rejects the modification to the
agreement, Israel would carry it out "by the book," or according
to Israeli interpretation, which analysts said would harm further
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
His extension of deadline was a retreat from an ultimatum he
issued Sunday night to the Palestinians after the negotiations hit
a snag over the release of Palestinian prisoners and the timetable
for a final Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his office, Barak threatened to halt
the negotiations and to implement the Wye agreement according to
Israeli interpretation if the Palestinians did not give
"satisfactory answers" within "the coming hours". Israeli sources
said the "coming hours" means until Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said the prime minister spoke with Arafat by
telephone Monday, but failed to break the current deadlock. The
deadline passed without any signs of Palestinian backing down.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have hoped to reach an agreement over the Wye
implementation before United States Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright starts a visit to the region on September 1 and to hold a
signing ceremony in Cairo, Egypt Thursday at her presence.
</P>
<P>
The main issues blocking a breakthrough were the release of
Palestinian prisoners and the timetable for Israeli troop
redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that Israel release 650 political
prisoners, those jailed for anti-Israel activities, but Israel
insists that it will release only 500 prisoners and will not free
those Palestinians involved in killings of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Barak has proposed to postpone the last of the three stages of
troop withdrawals stipulated in the Wye accord until February next
year, when the two sides are supposed to have worked out a
framework for the final-status talks, which deal with thorny
issues like Jerusalem and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians want Israel to complete all the troop
withdrawals at an earlier date in line with the original timetable
of the Wye accord, which calls on Israel to hand over 13 percent
of the West Bank to the Palestinians in three stages over a period
of 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Barak's hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu, who signed
the agreement with Arafat in October last year, carried out the
first stage of the agreement before freezing it in a failed
attempt to woo back rebellious coalition partners opposed to
territorial concession to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Barak's envoy Gilad Sher and senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat resumed talks in Jerusalem Monday afternoon, nearly
24 hours after Barak issued the ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
To help break the impasse, Osama el-Baz, senior adviser to
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, continued shuttling between the
Israeli and Palestinian sides Monday, meeting respectively with
Erekat and Sher.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian envoy held separate talks with Arafat and Barak
Sunday night and Monday, but was unable to bridge the gaps. Israel
Radio said Israel had rejected el-Baz's compromise proposal
calling on Israel to release more Palestinian prisoners and to
further specify the timetable for the troop withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
Since Barak's taking office early last month on a pledge to
move forward the peace process with the Arab neighbors, Egypt has
increased its role in mediating the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy accused the Palestinians
Monday of trying to create an atmosphere of crisis ahead of
Albright's visit by not agreeing to the Israeli proposals.
</P>
<P>
Barak has asked Washington to scale down its mediation role in
the peace process, but the Palestinians want the U.S. to continue
playing an active role.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current impasse, there were still signs that the
two sides were narrowing their gaps on the major issue of
Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by Barak's office Sunday night said
Israel would not release jailed members of Hamas or Islamic
Jihad, hinting that members of other Palestinian political groups
might be eligible for release.
</P>
<P>
Charging Barak of preparing to make concessions to the
Palestinians, former hawkish Israeli foreign minister Ariel Sharon
said Monday that Barak would be ready to release between 300 and
400 Palestinians "with Israeli bloods on their hands." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
