<HEADLINE> General: Blockade of Russian Peacekeepers in Kosovo Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 30 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian officer said
Monday that the blockade by Kosovar Albanians to prevent Russian
peacekeepers from entering Orahovac was "a thoroughly-planned
provocation" and a revenge on Russia for its march on Pristina
ahead of NATO troops in June.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians have maintained the roadblocks for a week and
talks to end the standoff have so far been fruitless.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant-General Nikolai Staskov, chief of staff of the
Russian airborne units, urged the NATO political leaders to exert
pressure on the Kosovar Albanians, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that "reason will prevail and our
peacekeepers will enter Orahovac without incident."
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that if attacked by Kosovars, "our
peacekeepers are prepared to use their weapons in self-defense."
</P>
<P>
The most important thing is "not to give in to provocation, in
as much as the operation will be jeopardized if there is
bloodshed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russian soldiers are scheduled to begin taking over from Dutch
troops as peacekeepers in Orahovac, about 40 kilometers southwest
of the provincial capital Pristina, but an advance party was
forced to turn back last Monday at one of the roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
About 3,600 Russians form part of the more than 40,000-strong
NATO-led Kosovo peacekeeping force (KFOR). 
</P>
</TEXT>
