<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi
Zuetir Monday asked the U.S. State of Secretary Madeleine Albright
to pressure Israel to end its daily aggression on the country.
</P>
<P>
Zuetir told the independent Central News Agency that Israel
usually escalates the situation in south Lebanon ahead of any
international envoy's visit to the region for reactivation of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
He added that Israeli's current aggression, which is aimed at
forcing Lebanon and Syria to accept its peace conditions, came
just before Albright kicks off her five-day tour to the region.
</P>
<P>
Albright will make her first visit to the Middle East later
this week since Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak took power in
July after ousting his hardline predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on Albright to help end the warfare in
south Lebanon by exerting pressure on Israel and pushing it to the
commitment to international laws.
</P>
<P>
On the weekend, tensions have been on the rise when Lebanese
guerrillas and Israeli troops escalated their fighting in the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Six Lebanese civilians were wounded and a Hezbollah fighter
killed during the fire exchange.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting
to oust Israeli troops out of the country. 
