<HEADLINE> Hamas Member Convicted of Directing Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 30 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli military court on
Monday convicted a member of the Islamic militant group Hamas of
masterminding two suicide bombings in downtown Jerusalem in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors asked the judges to give 24-year-old Ammar
al-Zibben 21 consecutive life-imprisonment sentences corresponding
to the number of Israelis killed in the two attacks.
</P>
<P>
The attacks were carried out by five Hamas suicide bombers at a
main open market and a popular pedestrian mall in the city.
</P>
<P>
Al-Zibben, from the West Bank town of Nablus, was arrested in
January 1998. The indictment said that he had served in the
Palestinian National Authority police force while being a member
of an underground Hamas cell.
</P>
<P>
He was also found guilty by the court of other operations,
including producing explosives and shooting at Israeli settlers,
Israeli radio reports said. Verdict for these convictions will be
handed down later this year.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, which opposes the Israeli-Palestinian peace making, has
killed scores of Israelis in a series of attacks it staged in
Israel since the signing of the historic Oslo peace accords in
1993.
</P>
<P>
Israel's security facilities have warned recently that Hamas
and other militant groups might renew terrorist attacks against
Israel as the stalled peace process was back on the track.
</P>
</TEXT>
