<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Finance Officials Discuss on Debt Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- A high-level seminar opened here
Monday to discuss and seek a lasting solution to Africa's debt
problem, which has long hindered the development of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the seminar is on the magnitude and effect of
Africa's debt problems, the role of foreign aid, sustainable
development and lessons of the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
 Botswanan President Festus G. Mogae said at the opening
ceremony, "the task at this meeting is an important and daunting
one: to come up solutions for the African debt problem." He
added, "The solution should reflect African needs and be
acceptable to the international financial community. "
</P>
<P>
He also noted that African countries should be realistic and
not expect unconditional debt write-offs.
</P>
<P>
"Africa currently faces an external debt of more than 285
million U.S. dollars, representing more than 200 percent of own
exports," said Mogae, also chairman of the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Among those attending the two-day conference are finance
ministers and governors of central banks from 18 African
countries, representatives from Japan, Britain, the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Actual debt service payments account for nearly one fourth of
governments' annual revenues and exceed annual expenditure on
health spending in 23 sub-Saharan African countries, according to
a report by United Nations Development Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Oil Sector Conquers Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Angola's petroleum industry has
resolved 95% of its potential Y2K problems as the new millennium
draws near, Angolan Vice-Minister of Science and Technology said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Sebastiao Teta was quoted by official radio station Radio
Nacional de Angola (RNA) as saying that the country's
petroliferous sector is in a state of "95% conformation" in
relation to the potential Y2K problems arising from shortsighted
design.
</P>
<P>
The reason for this progress is that the petroliferous
companies operating in Angola have been benefitting from
information exchanges and guarantees of their equipment providers,
Teta said.
</P>
<P>
But Teta expressed his anxiety for the financial sector, saying
that the government is worrying about the Y2K problems which may
affect the countability, salary processing, pension calculation,
bank transference and international banking business.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that thanks to an agreement signed with the World
Bank on the modernization of the country's information system,
changes and replacements of computers of the Angolan banks are
underway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
