<HEADLINE> 11 Countries Contribute Military Observers to UNOMSIL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
has agreed with a proposal by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
that 11 countries be added to the list of Member States
contributing military personnel to the United Nations Observer
Mission in Sierra Leone (UNOMSIL).
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Annan, which was published here Monday, the
president of the Security Council for the month of August, Martin
Andjaba of Namibia, said that the council members agreed with the
proposals contained in the letter from the Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
The 11 additional countries are Croatia, the Czech Republic,
Denmark, France, Indonesia, Nepal, Norway, Sweden, Thailand,
Tanzania and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council on August 20 authorized tripling the size
of UNOMSIL to help carry out a recent peace accord signed by the
Sierra Leonean Government and rebels in Lome, capital of Togo.
</P>
<P>
The increase to 210 military officers from 70 is the first step
toward a larger peacekeeping presence in the west African country
following the July 7 agreement between President Ahmad Kabbah and
Foday Sankoh, head of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
Although UNOMSIL has an authorized strength of 70, only about
50 military observers were deployed by the time when the Security
Council adopted the resolution on August 20. They were from 13
countries, including China, Egypt, Jordan, Kenya, New Zealand,
Russia and the United Kingdom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
