<HEADLINE> Egypt to Place Patrol Police in Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will place patrol police in
Greater Cairo in mid-September as part of the efforts to help
combat crimes and enhance stability, the interior minister said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Habib el-Adli told reporters that the patrol police system will
be applied on an experimental basis in the governorates of Cairo,
Giza and Qaliubia in the first stage.
</P>
<P>
It will later be expanded in other governorates after acquiring
experiences, el-Adli said.
</P>
<P>
"Stability already exists. It is to be strengthened," the
minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Each group of the patrol police will consist of an officer and
four policemen, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported. Its work
will be to support the security forces in the streets.
</P>
<P>
The policemen have received extensive training and will be
equipped with up-to-date communications equipment, cars and
motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
They will be under a special command at the Ministry of
Interior and under the direct responsibility of the security
directorates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
