<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent Aid Appealed for Sudan Hit By Fresh Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The International Federation of
Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies Monday warned donors that
more than 100,000 people are now in urgent of assistance as new
flooding worsens in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Federation had launched a 1.2-million-Swiss franc appeal to
support relief operations as flash floods spread to While Nile
State and destroyed another 800 houses, bringing the total number
of homes affected in nine states to over 20,000.
</P>
<P>
The Federation's Regional Delegation in the Kenyan capital
Nairobi said Monday in a media release that severe August
flooding has been caused by unusually heavy rains, with the level
of major rivers in the country exceedingly high for the time of
year.
</P>
<P>
So far, Khartoum State has suffered most, followed by River
Nile, North Kordofan, White Nile, Northern State and Sinnar, and
some 40 people are known to have died in flooding, said the
release.
</P>
<P>
Immediate needs of flood victims are shelter, blankets, medial
 intervention and access to clean water, the Federation said,
adding its appeal for urgent relief aid will strengthen a
Sudanese Red Crescent operation with limited in-country
resources.
</P>
<P>
Red Crescent workers are extremely concerned by deteriorating
health in stricken communities as diarrhoea disease is increasing
rapidly, helped by contaminated stagnant water.
</P>
<P>
Sprayers, chemicals and medical supplies are also urgently
required as flood water provides prime breeding sites for
mosquitoes, causing malaria among the victim, added the release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
