<HEADLINE> Rwanda Pledges Commitment to Lusaka Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Vice-President Paul
Kagame has reiterated Rwanda's commitment to the Lusaka accord,
saying that his country would pull its troops out of the Congo
immediately, if any one take up the responsibility to grant Rwanda
security.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliamentarians on Wednesday, Kagame, also the
defense minister, said the recent battle between Rwandan and
Uganda forces in Kisangani was a ''shame'' of the two friendly
countries, Rwandan News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the news agency, Kagame refused to comment on
allegations that Rwanda was the aggressor and had the intention to
oust rebel leader Ernest Wamba dia Wamba and his faction.
</P>
<P>
Kagame said the relations between Rwanda and Uganda have not
been affected by the Kisangani incidents, adding that leaders of
both countries are trying to investigate the cause and put in
place mechanisms so that the tragedy would not reoccur. 
</P>
