<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Announces Softwood Settlement With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Canadian International Trade
Minister Pierre Pettigrew Monday announced the settlement over a
softwood lumber dispute with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said, "I'm pleased that we have reached an
agreement, the resolution of which will allow B.C. lumber
producers to continue to perform strongly."
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, the two countries signed a settlement, under
which British Columbia's upper rate lumber exports to the United
States are limited to 110 million board feet.
</P>
<P>
Other limitations include the repricing of a certain amount of
lumber from the lower rate to the upper rate, which means that
B.C. lumber exporters will have to bear increased burdens of
stumpage fees.
</P>
<P>
The settlement will affect about 1 percent of B.C.'s total
lumber exports to the United States, while Alberta, Ontario and
Quebec, the other three dominant Canadian lumber export provinces,
will maintain their export allocation levels, according to
government sources.
</P>
<P>
The dispute began in January 1998, when the B.C. government
decided to reduce timber stumpage rates to offset the burden on
B.C. companies.
</P>
<P>
The United States accused Canada of breaching the Softwood
Lumber Agreement between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
