<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Optimistic About Congolese Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Congolese peace process
would be further enforced with all the rebel forces' endorsement
of the Lusaka cease- fire agreement, Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni said here Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
With the opposing factions of the rebel group the Congolese
Rally for Democracy (RCD) signing the accord on Tuesday, the
splintered armies would become friends with common enemies, the
president said while addressing the Parliament on the issue of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Uganda is happy with the reconciliation of the rebel groups and
hopes that they will take the implementation of the peace pact
seriously, he added.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said that a political committee comprising the foreign
 ministers of the players in the DRC issue would meet to discuss
the implementation of the Lusaka agreement following the rebels'
inking it.
</P>
<P>
When asked by some MPs about the pullout of Ugandan army from
the DRC, the president said that with the implementation of the
Lusaka agreement, the armed forces there would become
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Uganda's army presence in the DRC is for
security reasons, instead of economic ones as previously rumored
in some press reports.
</P>
<P>
On the recent clashes between Ugandan and Rwandan forces in
Kisangani, the third largest city in the DRC, he attributed it to
misunderstanding due to lack of communication. He, therefore,
stressed that the two armed forces there should strengthen
communication and trust each other.  
</P>
