<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Dennis Turns Seaward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Dennis turned out
to sea Monday after sideswiping the shoreline with 180 kph gusts
and up to 20.3 centimeters of rain that flooded streets and left
50,000 houses without power in North Carolina State of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Dennis kicked up 10-meter waves as it moved past Cape Fear on
its way out toward the open Atlantic, but the storm was expected
to stall off the North Carolina coast and could threaten the U.S.
East Coast for several days.
</P>
<P>
The hurricane was blamed for two traffic deaths early Monday.
Property damage appeared to be light, with shingles blown off some
homes, according to the North Carolina State Division of Emergency
Management.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, Dennis moved on a plodding course parallel to
the coasts of the Carolinas. Tens of thousands of residents and
tourists were evacuated from the barrier islands separated from
the mainland by roads that get swamped in storms.
</P>
<P>
On Monday afternoon, Dennis was 120 kilometers southeast of
Cape Hatteras, moving east-northeast at almost 32 kph with
sustained winds of nearly 145 kph, down from 170 kph in the
morning. A hurricane warning remained in effect for most of the
North Carolina coast to the Virginia State line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
