<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Report: "Orphan Drugs" Need "Foster Parents" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) now
proposes official regulatory status concerning drugs for
unprofitable diseases, known as "orphan" drugs, with full or
partial exemption fees, an exclusive marketing period of 10 years,
and help with clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
Euroabstracts, an EU publication, said in its August issue that
research on rare diseases will remain a priority under the EU's
fifth framework program for research and development.
</P>
<P>
Unprofitable diseases include those that are rare and those in
developing countries with no money to buy expensive medications.
</P>
<P>
"Producing affordable therapies for developing countries is
difficult, but for rare-disease sufferers there is more hope. By
changing legal constraints which affect profitability, we may
persuade pharmaceutical companies that rare diseases are worth
targeting," the EU said. It noted that the European parliament,
one of the EU branches, is tackling the issue.
</P>
<P>
The Euroabstracts said some EU member states, such as France,
Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Britain and Germany, have considered the
status of orphan drugs, but European harmonization and commercial
encouragement are lacking. So the EU needs to set up a kind of
protective mechanism for orphan drugs.
</P>
<P>
EU data shows that it costs an estimated 263 million U.S.
dollars to develop a new drug. If pharmaceutical companies cannot
sell cures to millions of people, they stand no chance of
recouping huge research costs, the EU study report said.
</P>
<P>
"So it's hardly surprising they concentrate on potential
best-sellers: drugs for heart disease, ulcers, diabetes,
Alzheimer's disease, the common cold," it said, adding the orphan
drugs are generally abandoned at birth.
</P>
<P>
Experts, however, do not believe rare diseases mean few
sufferers. They pointed out that the label "rare" is usually taken
to mean that a disease affects fewer than 7.5 people per 10,000.
This includes well-known scourges such as multiple sclerosis,
which affects some 500,000 people in Europe. The World Health
Organization estimates that there are around 5,000 rare diseases
in the world, affecting 20 million people.
</P>
<P>
Rare diseases can be difficult to diagnose because doctors tend
to be unfamiliar with them. They are also hard to cure: 50 to 80
percent are genetic in origin and require high-tech remedies such
as gene therapy rather than traditional organic chemistry. But EU
experts said most of the investment needed for gene therapy will
be in the development of basic techniques which serve as a
platform for other threatments.
</P>
<P>
In the matter of fact, basic research and development costs for
orphan drugs are much the same as for any other drugs. "To make
orphan drugs commercially attractive, something else will have to
change," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation in the United States, Japan and
Australia, the EU said their experience in lowering various
barriers should be learned because things in the three countries
show that orphan drugs can be profitable and the key is the
wholehearted "foster parents" for orphan drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
