<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Parliamentarians to Meet in Dhaka Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers from 36 Asian countries
will meet here Wednesday for a four-day conference in the
Bangladeshi capital Dhaka to explore avenues for mutual
cooperation to establish peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the conference, "Asian Parliamentarians'
Conference for Peace and Cooperation," is peace, which "is not
merely absence of war, conflict or violence. It is a state in
which each nation can flourish according to its own wish and
includes overall social and economic growth, removal of injustice,
respect for human rights and humanitarian laws, among other
factors."
</P>
<P>
Four papers on different subjects relating to peace will be
presented at the conference. The topics have been chosen in the
light of the Hague Agenda for Peace and Justice in the 21st
century which was adopted at an international conference held in
May this year.
</P>
<P>
The topics include: root causes of war and culture of peace,
international humanitarian and human rights law and institutions,
prevention, resolution and transformation of violent conflicts,
and disarmament and human security.
</P>
<P>
The conference is scheduled to be inaugurated by Bangladeshi
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina. The opposition parties, however,
have decided to boycott the meeting, which is expected to
culminate in forming an association of legislative bodies of Asian
Countries.
</P>
<P>
"We have already proposed formation of an Association of Asian
Parliaments for Peace for effective coordination among the
legislative bodies of the region," Bangladeshi Speaker Humayun
Rashid Chowdhury told reporters last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said the idea of holding such a conference came at the third
parliamentarians conference of SAARC (South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation) held in Dhaka in March this year. "Later we
decided to host the conference," he said.
</P>
<P>
A report in the Daily Star said the conference, on its
concluding day, is likely to come out with a declaration to be
named Dhaka Declaration, highlighting some specific objectives to
be realized through united efforts of parliaments of the region.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three countries have been invited, and 35 countries have
committed to attending the conference, funded by the Bangladeshi
government and the United Nations Development Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
