<HEADLINE> Vehicle Jacking Kills 15 in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 31 (Xinhua) -- At least 15 people were killed
and more than 19 others wounded when unidentified gunmen attacked
a public transport bus and a lorry in Mogadishu Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, more than 10 well-armed men riding a
Toyota pickup attacked the two vehicles in the jacking operation.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen attacked the bus which was transporting more than 60
people to villages north of Jowahar, a town some 90 kilometers
north of the capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of fire between the two sides had forced the
security guards of the vehicles to run for their lives, leaving
the bus in the hands of the attackers.
</P>
<P>
An eyewitness said that the gunmen threw the passengers one by
one out of the bus no matter what their status were. Some of the
passengers were dead while others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the attack is not known. However, sources close
to the militiamen said that the gunmen in north Mogadishu had
earlier forcefully stolen a vehicle belonging to the clansmen of
the gunmen who launched the Tuesday operation.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid controls the area where
the incident took place Tuesday, while those who looted the cars
belong to the faction of Ali Mahdi Mohamed. It doesn't seem that
neither of the two faction leaders fully controls the militiamen
in the areas they claim responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The jacking and clashes have worsened the security situation in
the capital of Somalia where there has been for long no central
administration since 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
