<HEADLINE> Arafat Looks For Dutch Role In Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat started his two-day visit to the Netherlands on Tuesday by
receiving a honorary award, a Dutch government official said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader received an honorary fellowship from the
Maastricht School of Management before meeting with Dutch Foreign
Minister Jozias van Aartsen.
</P>
<P>
There were no details regarding the discussions between Arafat
and the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Last week, when Arafat met with the Dutch foreign minister at
his Gaza office, he called for a greater European role in the
peace process, and for Dutch aid in the building of a Palestinian
port in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators last week discussed opening
the first Palestinian seaport and for passageways for Palestinians
between the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Van Aartsen said the Dutch government was considering
cooperation with the Palestinian Authority on justice matters. It
was said the Netherlands may offer aid to the Palestinians to
construct a police academy.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is expected to meet other high-ranking Dutch officials
on Wednesday, including Prime Minister Wim Kok, Development
Cooperation Minister Eveline Herfkens and Agricultural Minister
Laurens Jan Brinkhorst, the official from Netherlands Government
Information Service said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
