<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Palestinian Leaders Discuss Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on Tuesday held talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on the
latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Egypt's Mediterranean port city of
Alexandria, 220 kilometers northwest of Cairo, earlier in the day,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
His visit came amid reports that the Palestinians and Israelis
are close to an agreement on the implementation of the Wye peace
accord signed in October. Arafat left Alexandria after the talks.
</P>
<P>
It is possible that an agreement will be signed in Alexandria
on Thursday for the implementation of the Wye accord, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters after the meeting
between Mubarak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel "will intensify their negotiations
in the next few hours in an effort to reach a final formula for
the agreement," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Neither Arafat nor Mubarak spoke to reporters after their
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is reportedly hoping to host the signing ceremony of the
expected agreement on the implementation of the Wye accord during
the planned visit of Secretary of State of the United States
Madeleine Albright on Thursday within a regional tour.
</P>
<P>
Differences exist between the two sides over the timetable for
the Israeli troop pullback and the number of Palestinians to be
freed stipulated under the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that Israel release 650 political
prisoners, those jailed for anti-Israel activities. But Israel
insists that it will release only 500 prosoners and will not free
those Palestinians involved in killings of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has proposed to postpone the
last of the three-stage troop withdrawals stipulated in the Wye
accord until February next year, when the two sides are supposed
to have worked out a framework for the final-status talks, which
deal with thorny issues like Jerusalem and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians want Israel to complete all the troop
withdrawals at an earlier date in line with the original timetable
of the Wye accord, which calls on Israel to hand over 13 percent
of the West Bank over a period of 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Barak's hare-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu froze the Wye
accord late last December after carrying out the first stage of
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel in 1979, plays an active role to mediate the Arab-Israeli
peace talks, especially on the Palestinian track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Urges Improvement of Civil Law System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua)-- To guarantee the healthy
development of the socialist market economy with Chinese
characteristics, China's civil law system must be fine-tuned,
chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
Li's made the remark at the tenth legal talk given by legal
experts at the Great Hall of the People. The series of speeches
are organized to update senior official on developments in China's
legal system.
</P>
<P>
Li, who chaired today's talk, said that China has always
closely watched the building of the civil law system, adding that
the country's marriage law was drafted in the early 1950s, soon
after the founding of New China.
</P>
<P>
He said that the pace of promulgating civil laws and
regulations has quickened since the country adopted the reform and
opening-up policy in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that to meet the needs of future economic
development, China will continue to strengthen civil laws.
</P>
<P>
He urged that a property rights law be drafted and the marriage
law revised. He also said specific clauses should be added against
violation of personal and property rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
