<HEADLINE> Unionists May Try to Delay N. Irish Peace Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's main unionist
party, the Ulster Unionist Party, may call for next week's review
of the province's faltering peace accord to be delayed, said
political sources on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The party's leader David Trimble was planning to urge British
Prime Minister Tony Blair to postpone the review of problems
facing the Good Friday accord, the Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
UUP sources said the possibility of calling for a delay of the
review, to be chaired by U.S. mediator George Mitchell, would be
explored at Tuesday's meeting attended by UUP politicians.
</P>
<P>
The UUP was also expected to decide whether to mount a legal
challenge to last Thursday's ruling by Northern Ireland Secretary
Mo Mowlam that the Irish Republican Army has maintained a truce in
its long war against British rule, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Blair signaled on Tuesday that recent IRA death threats
against several teenagers in Northern Ireland would not change his
government's conviction that the guerrilla group's ceasefire was
holding. 
</P>
