<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Trade Growth is Weak in First Five Months of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's (EU)
trade growth with most of its partners was weak or declining in
the first five months of this year, EU statistics office, Eurostat,
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 15-country bloc's trade with the outside world was 2.6
billion euros (2.73 billion U.S. dollars) in May this year, down
from 5.9 billion euros (6.2 billion U.S. dollars) in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
There was a deficit of 11.5 billion euros (12 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first five months compared to a surplus of 3.2
billion euros (3.36 billion U.S. dollars) in the same period of
1998, the Eurostat said in a report.
</P>
<P>
There were signs of renewed growth in imports in May, mainly in
the "machinery and vehicles" sector, while exports continued to
fall, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
During the five-month period, exceptions were exports to China,
with an increase of 16 percent, and imports from Hungary with a 19
percent increase, the report shows.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, trade with Russia and Norway were weak, the
Eurostat indicated. From January to May, the EU's export with
Russia registered a decrease of 55 percent and a fall of 10
percent for imports. While trade with Norway recorded an 11
percent decrease for exports and 23 percent cut in imports.
</P>
<P>
Between January and May, Germany still enjoyed the largest
surplus of 25.3 billion euros (26.6 billion U.S. dollars), while
Britain's deficit rose to 20.3 billion euros (21.3 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat also estimated that the euro zone would have a
trade surplus of 8.7 billion euros (9.1 billion U.S. dollars) with
other parts of the world in June 1999, up 0.4 billion euros (0.42
billion U.S.dollars) from June last year. The euro zone is
composed of all EU countries but Britain, Denmark, Greece and
Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
