<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada is Shocked at Cyber Hacker Breach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Canada is shocked at a report
that Microsoft Corp. Monday admitted that cyber hackers had
overcome the security of a free e-mail service used by more than
40 million people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
There are 2.5 million Hotmail users in Canada, who have urged
for measures to prevent the biggest ever breach of consumer
privacy from happening again.
</P>
<P>
The National Post newspaper Tuesday quoted Canadian computer
science experts as saying: "There's no excuse for not having the
system secure."
</P>
<P>
According to the National Post, a copy of the so call "exploit"
was made available Monday to the newspaper, but Microsoft has
sealed the breach by that time and the exploit was ineffective.
</P>
<P>
The exploit, as termed by hackers, is referred to loopholes
which could be used by an unauthorized person to read, delete and
forward a Hotmail user's E-Mail.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft said Monday it had sealed up the hole in its Hotmail
service by 1:30 EDT, and no instances were reported of consumers
losing sensitive information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
