<HEADLINE> UK's Blair Considers IRA Cease-fire Holding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Tuesday indicated that recent death threats from the IRA (Irish
Republican Army) would not change his government's conviction that
the guerrilla group's cease-fire in Northern Ireland was holding.
</P>
<P>
In the last three days, the IRA has ordered six Catholic
teenagers to leave Northern Ireland under threat of death.
</P>
<P>
While describing the death threats as "totally indefensible," a
spokesman for Blair said on Tuesday that similar activities, like
punishment beatings, had continued all the way through the IRA's
last cease-fire, which broke down in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman said former U.S. Senator George Mitchell was
ready to launch his review of the province's stalled peace process
on Monday but would first be seeking assurances from all parties
that they remained committed to it, according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
Unionists reportedly will meet on Tuesday to decide whether to
take part in the review and whether to mount a court challenge to
Mowlam's ruling on the IRA cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Blair's office also signaled that he stood firmly behind Mowlam,
despite Unionist calls for her resignation, as the spokesman said:
"The Secretary of State has done one of the most difficult jobs in
government extremely well and continues to do so."
</P>
<P>
Blair, fresh back from holiday, will talk to his Northern
Ireland minister, Mo Mowlam, later in the day, Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
"He was fully consulted and fully supported the statement she
made last week," the spokesman was quoted saying. "He supports
that 100 percent."
</P>
<P>
Mowlam angered pro-British Ulster Unionists by ruling the Irish
Republican Army had not broken a two-year-old cease-fire despite
alleged links to the murder of a Belfast man and a plot to smuggle
guns from the United States, according to earlier reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
