<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang's Visit to Bring Sino-Thai Relations Into New Era (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 31 (Xinhua) - The friendly relations between
China and Thailand are expected to enter a new era as Chinese
President Jiang Zemin makes a state visit to Thailand this week.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin, who will visit Thailand from September 2-
6, will be the only foreign dignitary who has been invited by Thai
King Bhumibol Adulyadej to visit Thailand this year before the
king's 72nd, or sixth cycle, birthday on December 5.
</P>
<P>
China and Thailand have enjoyed long-standing friendship since
ancient times. After the establishment of diplomatic relations in
1975, the two countries quickened the pace of developing friendly
relations in all areas.
</P>
<P>
Sharing similar or identical views on key international issues,
China and Thailand maintain good cooperation in dealing with
regional and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
It is widely known that Sino-Thai relations have become a model
for countries with different social systems to develop mutually
beneficial, cooperative, friendly and good neighborly relations.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a joint statement on the Plan of
Action for the 21st century early this year when Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan visited Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The plan sets the direction for political, economic and social
cooperation between the two countries for the next 100 years. It
will also serve as a blueprint to be followed by government
agencies in both countries in order to maximize cooperation during
the next century.
</P>
<P>
Politically, the two countries have been strengthening ties
through a frequent exchange of high level visits this year.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, Chairman of China's National People's Congress visited
Thailand in April, and Thai Princess Sirindhorn paid her ninth
visit to China in the same month with Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai following in step.
</P>
<P>
And now, the highest level visit by President Jiang will
further promote the development of bilateral relations, according
to the Thai prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Beyond politics, China and Thailand have also developed strong
economic and trade relations. Bilateral trade increased to 3.56
billion U.S. dollars from 24.6 million dollars when diplomatic
relations were first established.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have managed to keep a balance in bilateral
trade.
</P>
<P>
China's exports to Thailand have expanded from traditional
Chinese medicine, light industrial products and crude oil to
mechanical equipment, engines, electricity generators, machine
tools and steel products.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand's exports to China go beyond traditional
products.
</P>
<P>
Economic cooperation between the two countries is no longer
limited to trade. Thailand is an important investor in China with
more than 2,000 investment projects worth more than one billion
dollars, while Chinese companies are active in bidding on projects
in Thailand. More
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang's Visit to Bring Sino-Thai Relations Into New Era (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two countries have also beefed up their cooperation in
scientific research. A joint committee, set up in 1978, meets
annually to encourage scientists from both countries to launch
joint research projects in the fields of agriculture, medicine,
food, mining, transportation biology and information technology.
</P>
<P>
Cultural exchanges are developing smoothly thanks to a
memorandum of understanding on cultural exchange and cooperation
signed by the two countries in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, as the Chinese people celebrate the 50th anniversary
of the founding of the People's Republic of China and the Thai
people preparing for their king's sixth cycle birthday, several
cultural groups from both countries have visited each other to
commemorate the great events.
</P>
<P>
As China's economy keeps growing, more and more Chinese people
visit Thailand. The kingdom has become the top destination when
Chinese want to go abroad for a holiday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, more than 600,000 Chinese visited Thailand. China is
expected to become the largest overseas tourism market for
Thailand within the next three years, a Thai tourism official
predicted.
</P>
<P>
It is shared by both Thai and Chinese sides that the
development of an "all-weather, all-dimension" relationship is in
the interests of the two peoples and also conducive to the peace,
stability and development of the region.
</P>
<P>
As the world is about to enter a new millennium, the visit paid
by China's highest official to Thailand will be, as Thai Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai said, "a historical landmark" in bilateral
relations that will initiate a new era of comprehensive
cooperation and common development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
