<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Host Inaugural Meeting to Launch East Asia-Latin America Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman from Singapore's
Ministry of Foreign Affairs announced here Tuesday that the
inaugural meeting of officials to launch the East Asia-Latin
America Forum (EALAF) mooted by Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong will take place here from September 1 to 3, and 27 East Asian
and Latin American countries will be represented at the event.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman quoted the prime minister as saying Tuesday that
he is encouraged with the level of support for the forum and
pleased to see the initiative get off ground quickly.
</P>
<P>
"This shows that all participating countries welcome the need
for formal dialogue and cooperation between our regions. I hope,
over time, regular contacts will connect our regions which have
been separated by history and geography," the prime minister was
quoted.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the meeting will launch a process of
multi-dimensional dialogue and cooperation between East Asia and
Latin America and the three objectives of the meeting are to
discuss the strategic rationale for the forum to link East Asia
and Latin America and its multi-dimensional structure, to start
the preparatory process for the second meeting of the Forum at the
foreign minister's level that will take place in about one year
and to discuss concrete projects of cooperation among the forum's
participating countries.
</P>
<P>
The project of the forum was first put forth by Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong during his visit to Chile in October 1998 and the
idea met with active response from relative countries, the
spokesman said, adding that countries attending the inaugural
meeting are Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador,
Mexico, Panama, Paraguay, Peru, Uruguay, Venezuela, Singapore,
Brunei, Cambodia, Thailand, Vietnam, the Philippines, Malaysia,
Laos, Indonesia, Myanmar, Japan, China, South Korea, Australia and
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Goh conceived the forum as a
multi-dimensional dialogue to help break down barriers and
encourage the evolution of more concrete links between East Asia
and Latin America and he believes the forum will contribute to a
stable international order by interconnecting two important growth
areas of the world.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister had said the potential of linking
the two regions is likely to take 10 years or more due to the lack
of historic contact, awareness and understanding between both
regions and the launch of the forum will thus be the start of a
long-term process to bring that synergy to fruition, the spokesman
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
