<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Ruling Party Leader Relieved of Party Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Akhtaruzzaman Chowdhury Babu,
commerce and industries secretary of the ruling Bangladesh Awami
League, who allegedly forced the chairman and other directors of a
bank to resign and declared himself as the new chairman of the
bank, has been relieved of his responsibility, a party press
release said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Babu, a former member of parliament, has been stripped of the
party responsibility for his activities against the ideals,
programs, constitution, rules and regulations and the interest of
the Awami League, said a press release signed by Abdul Mannan
Khan, office secretary of the party.
</P>
<P>
Eight directors of the United Commercial Bank Limited (UCBL)
were discussing matters of the bank at a meeting last Thursday
when Babu and some armed supporters reportedly broke into the
board room and forced the directors to resign.
</P>
<P>
The head office of the UCBL in the city's Motijheel commercial
area was sealed by police and put under police custody the next
day, and an administrator from the central Bangladesh Bank was
appointed.
</P>
<P>
The High Court, acting upon a writ petition filed by UCBL
Chairman Zafar Ahmed Chowdhury, later stayed the order of the
Bangladesh Bank, allowed Ahmed Chowdhury and the directors to
carry out their functions and asked the central bank to present an
inquiry report of the bank incident.
</P>
<P>
The UCBL, a private bank, has 79 branches throughout the
country with a deposit of 11 billion taka (220 million U.S.
dollars) and employing more than 2,500 people, according to Zafar
Ahmed Chowdhury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
