<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technological Innovation Top Agenda of China's Scientific Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of China's science and
technology programs are speeding up the drafting of their five-
year development plan in the next century, putting technological
innovation at the top of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Science and Technology Zhu Lilan said that the 10th
five-year scientific development program (2001-2005) will center
on expanding the contribution of science development to economic
growth, increasing the share of added-value of high-tech ventures
among all industrial enterprises, and increasing export volumes
from high-tech ventures.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said this last week in Beijing during discussions with some
of the country's legislators who were participating in a national
conference on technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told members of the Education, Science, Culture and Health
Committee under the National People's Congress (NPC), the country'
s top legislature, that there are several major areas of focus for
the 10th five-year development program: pushing ahead the
agricultural scientific revolutionary process; raising the
technological level of the industrial ventures in a bid to boost
the growth of high-tech ventures; encouraging sustainable
development; upgrading traditional industries, developing
technologies for the service sector, environmental protection and
comprehensive utilization of resources; and promoting development
of technology for use in both military and civilian fields.
</P>
<P>
China plans to turn nearly all research and development
institutes into technology-based ventures by the end of the year
2000 in order to get most scientists and technicians directly
involved in technological developments and their industrial use.
</P>
<P>
Later this year, the ministry will host a national conference
on the work to spread scientific knowledge while wiping out
superstitious thinking among the public, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Echoing the minister's call for support, Peng Peiyun, vice-
chairwoman of the NPC Standing Committee, said that the NPC is
considering drafting a law on promoting hi-tech industrial zones
in China, as well as other laws concerning scientific and
technological development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
