<HEADLINE> China to Play Greater Role in World Philately, FIP President (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- China can be the backbone of the
world's philatelic sector in the 21st century, according to the
president of the Federation of International Philately (FIP).
</P>
<P>
Knud Mohr made the comments in a winding up address at the
China 1999 World Philatelic Exhibition, which ended yesterday in
Beijing, and also praised the Chinese organising committee of the
event for its efforts in making the exhibition a huge success.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the worldwide experts and exhibition visitors were
pleasantly surprised at the smooth organization," said Mohr in an
exclusive interview with Xinhua. "China has most definitely
demonstrated it has the ability to host such important world
events."
</P>
<P>
"Staging the FIP's flagship event in China was a historic
milestone in the philatelic world," added Mohr.
</P>
<P>
The aims of the FIP, which was founded on June 18, 1926, are to
popularize philately throughout the world and arouse people's
interest in stamp collecting, the 62-year-old Danish philatelist
explained.
</P>
<P>
"And despite only being formed 17 years ago the All China
Philatelic Federation (ACPF) is already recognised as a model in
the philatelic circle," he said.
</P>
<P>
"All those involved with this young organization should be
praised for their excellent work during the 10-day event," Mr Mohr
went on.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits were world class and included the original artist'
s designs of the famous British Penny Black, the world's first
stamp, as well as other unique stamps and envelopes owned by
famous philatelists.
</P>
<P>
"From the 1996 Asia Philatelic Exhibition, which was also held
in China, to the FIP exhibition, the focus of world philately has
been shifted to Asian countries, especially China, which boasts 20
million stamp collectors," Mohr said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Palm Held Aircraft Developed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A miniature multi-purpose
aircraft that can land and take off from the palm of a hand has
been developed in China.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the new product, the first of its kind in
China, can be used for both military and civilian purposes, such
as making a reconnaissance of enemy positions, locating victims of
disasters, patrolling pastures and monitoring traffic and
environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, developed by the Nanjing University of
Aeronautics and Astronautics (NUAA) in east China's Jiangsu
Province, weighs only 350 grams and has a width of 45 centimeters
when both wings are fully outstretched.
</P>
<P>
The radio-controlled aircraft, equipped with a gas engine, has
a top speed of 80 km per hour and can fly nonstop for 20 minutes
within a radius of 1,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
A video camera and transmitter attached to its underbelly
enable simultaneously taking and sending pictures of objects on
the ground to a receiver when it is in flight.
</P>
<P>
During a demonstration flight here today, the tiny aircraft
took off smoothly and looped and circled in the air. A ground
monitor showed pictures of buildings, streets, fields and even
moving vehicles that the aircraft was photographing.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Guoming, who is in charge of the development of the project,
said that the miniature aircraft differs from a model plane mainly
because it has an automatic stabilizing system and is controlled
by means of a camera installed on the plane instead of the human
eye. It will be further improved to gain more functions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Great attention has been paid to the development of miniature
aircraft worldwide in recent years. The smallest aircraft in the
world is only 15 centimeters in width.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Play Greater Role in World Philately, FIP President (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As modern postal services originated in European countries,
philately developed early there and collectors were able to obtain
many rare stamps and others items at fairly low prices.
</P>
<P>
"Asian people expect to pay much more for their collections,"
Mohr said.
</P>
<P>
However, the booming stamp trade could help philatelists all
over the world, including those in China, buy foreign and even
rare stamps.
</P>
<P>
"Most European and American youngsters are currently pre-
occupied with ultra-modern activities such as surfing the web and
computer games," Mohr said. "They simply do not have the patience
to sit silently and just enjoy the many varied and colorful stamps.
</P>
<P>
"However, the Chinese young people still find enjoyment in
collecting stamps. Indeed, many of them develop their personality
and creativity through philately."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the fact that some people regard stamp collecting
as an investment, Mohr said, "It's true that collecting can be an
investment, but first and foremost it is a personal hobby."
</P>
<P>
"If a collector is always assessing the profits made from
trading or worries about the devaluation of stamps, he loses the
joy of the hobby," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mohr also said he is not surprised at the success of Chinese
philatelists in the FIP championships during the exhibition. "They
demonstrated high standards of stamp albums to international
jurors and visitors," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
