<HEADLINE> Unstoppable Yao Ming Slams Down Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUKUOKA, Japan, August 31 (Xinhua) -- He had the game, as we
always said, in a perfect way.
</P>
<P>
The NBA prospect Yao Ming scored 20 points in 20 minutes to
help tournament favorites China to a 91-54 crash of Kuwait in the
quarter-final round at the Asian men's Basketball Championships
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 2.28-meter center, 19, drilled in all nine field baskets
and two free-throws, including five slams, and grabbed six
rebounds plus three blocks in a half-time play, with Kuwait having
nothing to stop his dominance in the paint.
</P>
<P>
China's another pivot Wang Zhizhi led the game with 23 points
through a second-half performance as the Chinese squad used two
different lines-up in each half to beat up Kuwait for its third
consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
"Every one had the equal opportunity on the court," said China'
s head coach Jiang Xingquan. "We played an excellent inside game
against the smaller Kuwait's team."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's top-scorer Mubarak Osamah chipped in 16 points and was
outrebounded 23-45.
</P>
<P>
A brawl in a game between Lebanon and Saudi Arabia scared the
so far mild-tempered competition with Lebanon having its semi-
final dream severely damped after a 92-69 defeat.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Khatib Fadi slapped flagrantly into Fallath Mokhtar's
face when Mokhtar was dribbling towards the basket with 34 seconds
left in the game. There were some shoves and pushes before the
two were broke away by teammates.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, who surprised reigning champions South Korea 75-65 on
Sunday, virtually gave up the match after the brawl.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei had its unbeatable run snapped when its was
edged off by South Korea, 61-54, in a hard-fought match, while
Japan downed Syria 78-58 in another quarter-final match.
</P>
<P>
In the classification playoffs, the United Arab Emirates
squeezed through by a 79-72 win over Bahrain, Hong Kong of China
won its first game in the competition, a 89-59 triumph over
Malaysia, and Uzbekistan overcame Philippines 94-64. 
</P>
