<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiations to Sell South Korean Bank Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government failed
to sell the Seoulbank to HSBC as negotiations collapsed Tuesday on
huge differences over terms of the deal, said a statement from the
Financial Supervisory Commission (FSC).
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum signed February 22 with HSBC, the South Korean
government showed its intent to sell the Seoulbank to the British
bank.
</P>
<P>
The FSC said in a statement that the talks had broken down on
huge differences over how to value the Seoulbank's assets and
future loan portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The FSC said the government would turn to renowned foreign
experts to have them manage Seoulbank and invest 4 to 5 trillion
won (3.33 to 4.17 billion U.S. dollars) to get it back on the
right track. State shares of the Seoulbank will be sold on
international financial markets.
</P>
<P>
After the financial crisis, the government decided to sell off
the Seoulbank and the Korea First Bank to foreign investors. So
far, a sale agreement in the amount of 600 million U.S. dollars
has been made between the Korea First Bank and a U.S. investment
consortium Newbridge Capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen, Vanuatu Deputy PM Confer in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
said here today that China places great importance on its
relations with Vanuatu, and is ready to work with Vanuatu to
further bilateral ties based on mutual respect, mutual trust,
equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during talks with Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister for Trade, Tourism and Business Development Willie Jimmy
of the Republic of Vanuatu.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed to the smooth development of bilateral ties since
the establishment of diplomatic relations 17 years ago, and said
that the two countries have maintained constant high-level
exchanges of visit, and thus promoted mutual understanding,
friendship and bilateral ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
