<HEADLINE> Pakistan Opposed to Any Plan to Undermine Iraq's Sovereignty: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Tuesday expressed Pakistan's opposition to any plan to
undermine Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Speaker of the Iraqi National
Assembly Sa'doon Hammadi, Sharif said, "Pakistan would strongly
oppose any plan to undermine Iraq's sovereignty and territorial
integrity."
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed the hope that the countries in the Gulf region
would evolve a regime towards confidence building to overcome the
legacy of the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Pakistani government and people were "deeply
distressed at the magnitude of human sufferings in Iraq caused by
eight-year-long U.N. sanctions."
</P>
<P>
These sufferings, Sharif said, should be alleviated "as early
as possible."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister reiterated Pakistan's position that problems
in the region should be solved peacefully through diplomatic
efforts and not through use of force.
</P>
<P>
He agreed with the need to reinvigorate cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi, who is visiting Pakistan at the head of a six-member
Iraqi parliamentary delegation, conveyed the desire of the Iraqi
government to re-energize bilateral relations with Pakistan,
consistent with the wishes of its people.
</P>
<P>
In this context, he referred to the goodwill which has all
along existed between the people of Iraq and Pakistan and the
potential for enhanced cooperation particularly in the economic
sphere.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi speaker also briefed Sharif on the situation faced by
Iraq as a consequence of U.N. economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq has already fulfilled all conditions set forth in
the U.N. Security Council resolutions particularly those relating
to the elimination of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"It was, therefore, obligatory that all sanctions imposed on
Iraq be lifted as provided in the U.N. resolutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi recounted repeated attempts to prolong the sanctions
and to undermine Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
