</P>
<P>
-- There were indications Monday that Israel would release at
least some prisoners of two Palestinian rejectionist groups as
part of the Wye negotiations, once it is convinced that the
prisoners and the groups they represent will cease the armed
struggle against Israel and join the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The groups are the Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine and the Popular Front of the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak will try to convince PNA
Chairman Yasser Arafat Tuesday to give his assent to an agreement
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Prime Minister Ehud Barak will sign the agreement in
Egypt Thursday at the presence of U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright if the PNA chairman nods approval.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian position is that Israel's proposals on the
implementation of the Wye accord are reasonable and the
Palestinians should accept them and begin the implementation.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli police have launched a wide-ranging investigation
after two Israelis were found murdered near the West Bank Monday,
saying the possibility of a nationalist motive behind the killing
could not be ruled out. Barak expressed shock Monday night at the
murder of Yehezkel Shai, 26, and his girlfriend, Sharon Steinmetz,
21, and called on police to make every effort to catch the
perpetrators,
</P>
<P>
Yediot Ahronot:
</P>
<P>
-- The budget cut proposed by the Finance Ministry of Israel is
much harsher than previously published. At least 11 ministers have
been threatening to prevent the approval of the 2000 budget next
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Treasury officials are preparing "alternatives" to the proposed
cuts, including imposing tax on rent and cigarettes, if the budget
is not approved. 
</P>
