<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Threatens to Withdraw Process of KR Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. legal team
threatened Wednesday to cease its efforts to try former Khmer
Rouge leaders if the government of Cambodia can not meet the
conditions put forward by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Ralph Zacklin, assistant to the U.N. secretary general, told
reporters at a press conference here that "if the government is
not able to meet the conditions which the United Nations believes
are necessary for a tribunal that would be up to international
standard, the U.N. will simply cease to follow the process."
</P>
<P>
He added, "The government of Cambodia, of course, can proceed
on its own, to adopt the law, to set up a tribunal and even
receive assistance from outside, such as NGOs and individuals, but
not the assistance from the U.N."
</P>
<P>
No agreement was reached so far between the Cambodian and U.N.
legal groups on the establishment of a tribunal to try former
Khmer Rouge leaders. The two sides have held two rounds of talks
since the U.N. five-member legal team arrived in Phnom Penh on
August 25.
</P>
<P>
Zacklin said that "there is, at the present time, very wide
divergence in views as the nature of the tribunal we are talking
about." But he pointed out that both sides have the feeling that
it is important to continue the discussions in the efforts to find
some common grounds.
</P>
<P>
"The next step in this process", said Zacklin, "will be the
visit of Prime Minister Hun Sen to New York, and on that
occasion, we expect that the position of the Cambodian government
with regards to the U.N. proposal will be made clear."
</P>
<P>
The two sides differed mainly on the nature of the tribunal and
on who will have a majority of the judges. The Cambodian side
insisted on a municipal court with a majority of Cambodian judges
while the U.N. demanded forming an international-style ad hoc
tribunal in Cambodia with judges and prosecutors appointed by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Zacklin also said that the international assistance provided to
such a tribunal by judges, prosecutors and investigators and other
experts should not be seen as a violation of Cambodia's
sovereignty "but rather a contribution by the international
community to the Cambodian government and Cambodian people".
</P>
<P>
He referred to Prime Minister Hun Sen's warning early this
month that the U.N. should not violate Cambodia's sovereignty
which is also a member of the U.N., citing the U.N. wanted to
dominate the Cambodian court and procedure.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. legal team is to return New York Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
