<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militiaman Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A member of the pro-Israeli
South Lebanon Army (SLA) was wounded Tuesday in south Lebanon
during Lebanese guerrillas' attacks, Lebanese security sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The militiaman was slightly hurt when his outpost at Arab
Salim village on the verge of the Israeli occupied border zone in
south Lebanon was hit by mortar rounds.
</P>
<P>
There has been no group claiming responsibility for the
attack, which has raised to 45 the number of SLA members wounded
in south Lebanon since the start of this year while another nine
members were killed.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been
spearheading a guerrillas' war to oust the Israeli occupation
troops and their allied SLA out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
