<HEADLINE> China to Step Up Ecotourism Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
adopting measures to develop ecotourism in a bid to ensure the
sustained development of its tourism industry, a senior official
has said.
</P>
<P>
He Guangwei, director of China's National Tourism
Administration, made the remark at an ongoing symposium on
ecotourism in Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan
Province.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium, which has been organized by the
administration and the World Tourism Organization, opened Monday
and was attended by Secretary-General Francesco Frangialli of the
international organization and a wide range of experts and
scholars.
</P>
<P>
He Guangwei pointed out that China, with abundant resources,
has the potential to develop ecotourism. So far, China has
established 700 nature reserves and 14 of them have joined the "
World Biosphere Network".
</P>
<P>
China has already made tourism a new growth area for promoting
the development of the national economy, creating job
opportunities and eliminating poverty.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's tourism sector reported a foreign exchange
income of 12.6 billion U.S. dollars from 63.49 million overseas
tourists. The number of domestic tourists reached 690 million in
the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
