<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Out to Address Long-term Manpower Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Tuesday launched the
Manpower 21, the overall integrated strategy of the country's
long-term development of work force, gearing up to address
challenges of the new millennium in manpower development with a
vision to turn the city state into a Talent Capital.
</P>
<P>
Manpower 21 is a blueprint covering the full manpower spectrum
and aimed at developing a globally competitive work force in
Singapore to power the country into a knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
Six core strategies are listed in the plan to address various
aspects of the manpower value chain, including manpower planning,
lifelong learning, talent augmentation, manpower development,
workplace transformation and partnership in the face of rapid
advances in technology, and a constantly changing, highly
competitive external environment.
</P>
<P>
Under the Manpower 21, a ministerial-level national manpower
council will be created to set directions for manpower development
and oversee national manpower planning, manpower development and
talent attraction.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony, Singapore Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong said the Manpower 21 aims to transform
Singapore's work force to meet future manpower needs, enhance
competitiveness and minimize structural unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Lee said the centerpiece of the Manpower 21 is the idea of a
"school of lifelong learning" and this is a comprehensive
framework for in-employment education and training.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government will set up a dedicated manpower
development assistance scheme with initial funding of 200 million
Singapore dollars, expand the manpower development scheme and
continue to support the Skill Development Fund.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the urgency of manpower development, Lee said
although the economy is picking up again, companies are still
restructuring their operations and retrenching workers, especially
in the disk and PC industries.
</P>
<P>
He was believed to be referring to the recent retrenchment
exercises by some multinational companies in his country. In the
last few weeks alone in Singapore, Western Digital has announced
2,500 retrenchments, Seagate has been reported to be planning to
retrench 1,600 workers and Compaq decided to lay off 1,600
workers.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Minister for Manpower Lee Boon Yang emphasized
the work to develop safe and healthy work environment with strong
tripartite (government-employer-union) relations and sound human
resources practices.
</P>
<P>
He also attached great importance to attracting appropriate
foreign manpower to supplement homegrown manpower resources and
viewed it as a solution to the problem of Singapore's limited
manpower resources that hampers the economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
