<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Discuss Palestinian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on Tuesday held talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on the
latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Egypt's Mediterranean port city of Alexandria
earlier in the day, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
His visit came amid reports that the Palestinians and Israelis
are close to an agreement on the implementation of the Wye peace
accord signed in October.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, a frequent visitor to Egypt, turned to Mubarak, a
trusted adviser, for consultations on the peace negotiations with
Israel at this critical stage.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is reportedly in the hope of hosting the signing ceremony
of the expected agreement on the implementation of the Wye accord
during a visit to the region by Secretary of State of the United
States Madeleine Albright to start on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to repeat his visit to Egypt on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye accord, Israel should, among other things, pull
back troops from another 11 percent of the West Bank in the last
two of the three-phased withdrawals, and release hundreds of
Palestinian political prisoners held in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Differences still exist between the two sides over the
timetable for the Israeli troop pullback and the number of
Palestinians to be freed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
