<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said here Tuesday that Russia strives to establish a multipolar
world that "must be based on the principles and norms of
international law and the mutual interests of all states."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony of the credentials presentation by 12
ambassadors in the Kremlin, Yeltsin said that the world community
"is faced with a strategic choice of its future" at the threshold
of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"The main task to be tackled now is the creation of multipolar
world which must be based on the principles and norms of
international law and the mutual interests of all states," the
Interfax news agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that Russia's goals are the development of
international relations on a democratic basis, the strengthening
of global stability and security, and the enhancement of the role
of the United Nations." 
