<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Keep Lower Deficit Till 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
vowed to keep a lower public sector deficit until next year, a
senior financial official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said in a press briefing
that the government move shows that it does not want to sacrifice
the nation's economic growth it has attained under the new
administration.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the country has only 2.2 percent deficit of GNP
while other Asian countries now experience between 3.5 to 5
percent deficit in their GNP, Philippine News Agency (PNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the International Monetary fund (IMF) has given the
country a two-year leeway to tackle the said deficit and keep the
economic fundamentals intact, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, it will be incumbent on the part of the government to
make the necessary adjustments in its economic targets for the
years 2000 and 2001 should there be changes in the economic path
the country is treading.
</P>
<P>
But one sure thing is that the IMF will still allow the country
to overshoot its 68-billion-peso (1.7-billion-U.S. dollar) target
deficit because of the leeway given by the IMF, he said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the IMF has allowed other countries to have ample
leeway which is much bigger than that of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He said that even if there is visible proof of lesser revenue
collection, the government will still pursue its pump-priming
efforts in order to keep the programs of the new administration in
place.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, the country's economic problems are basically
different from those of the other countries in the region," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
Vis-a-vis the GNP, the Philippines' public sector deficit is
still moderate compared with the neighboring economies which were
battered by the recent onslaught of the crisis, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
