<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Blames Donors for Africa's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Tuesday blamed
donor countries for Africa's economic morass, saying that the
constant changing of goalposts by donors has made it difficult for
Africa to repay its debts.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Tuesday quoted president Daniel arap
Moi as saying that the use of corruption as an excuse for
suspending funds was unfair, for no country in the world can say
it has got rid of this old vice.
</P>
<P>
Moi said the adage "he who plays the piper calls the tune"
mirrors exactly the relationship between developed and developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
He questioned the sincerity of donor agencies when addressing a
high- level seminar on Africa's external debt, which was attended
by financial ministers and governors of central banks from 17
African countries.
</P>
<P>
"How can African countries be expected to be up-to-date with
foreign debt repayments when illegal arms brought in from
developed countries continue to create instability thereby
hampering economic development?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa currently faces an external debt of more than 285
billion U.S. dollars, representing over 200 percent of its own
exports, according to World Bank statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
