<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Embark on Moral Rebirth Crusade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to launch a national
moral and ethical rebirth program on September 9, in a bid to
promote positive attitudinal change among Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The launch is expected to flag off the "new dawn" promised by
President Olusegun Obasanjo in his inaugural speech on May 29,
this year, according to Tuesday's "New Nigerian" newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Onyema Ugochuwu, a senior special assistant to
the president on National Orientation and Public Affairs, as
saying that the moral campaign was aimed at cleansing Nigeria of
all the vices that have bedeviled the country in recent years
such as corruption, dishonesty and lack of transparency in public
and private affairs.
</P>
<P>
Lamenting what he described as negative influences
institutionalized by years of military rule, he observed that
people have been viewing government with cynicism and skepticism
because past governments failed to keep faith with the people by
providing good governance.
</P>
<P>
The high level of corruption in Nigeria has even been elevated
to an official policy, he said. People openly demanded and
received bribes, he said, adding the culture of corruption has
scared away foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The president's aid said that the program of moral rebirth
would be launched as a demonstration of the president's
determination to eradicate such social ills to enable Nigeria to
move forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
