<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarket falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
suffered its third consecutive fall Tuesday with key blue chips
all on the decline.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the possibility of more interest rate rises in the
United States was still making investors on the local stock market
cautious.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed 41.1 points, or 1.37 percent, down to
2,951.9.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials also suffered, slipping 76.7 points to
5,115.7 and the all resources finished 10.9 points lower at
1,254.1.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank dropped 79.7 cents to 15.1 U.S.
dollars, Westpac bank 17.7 cents to 6.05 U.S. dollars, the
Commonwealth bank 22.4 cents to 15.71 U.S. dollars and ANZ bank 3
cents to 6.49 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Big communications companies Telstra Corp. and Cable &AMP; Wireless
Optus also led the telco sector down. Telstra finished 10 cents
lower at 5.19 U.S. dollars and C&AMP;W Optus eased 8 cents to 2.18
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resource giants Rio Tinto and BHP dragged the mining sector
into negative territory. Rio fell 16 cents to 17.14 U.S. dollars
and BHP dropped 26.1 cents to 11.08 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 376.3 million shares traded for a value
of 683 million U.S. dollars. There were 448 rising stocks and 783
falling ones while 462 were steady. 
</P>
