<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Vanuatu Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji met
with Willie Jimmy, deputy prime minister and minister of Trade,
Tourism and Business Development of Vanuatu, here this afternoon
at the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that bilateral ties between China and Vanuatu, a tiny
Pacific island, have witnessed smooth growth since the two forged
diplomatic ties in 1982. "With frequent high-level reciprocal
visits, the two countries have enhanced mutual understanding and
friendship, and bilateral cooperation in the economic, trade and
education sectors scored fruitful results," he said.
</P>
<P>
Vanuatu opened an honorary consulate in Beijing yesterday. Zhu
considered the move beneficial to make bilateral ties closer.
</P>
<P>
Both developing countries, China and Vanuatu share common views
in many global and regional affairs and have cooperated with each
other in international and regional organizations, including the
South-Pacific Forum (SPF), he said, adding that the further
enhancement of such ties were in the fundamental interests of the
two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The consolidation of ties between China and other developing
countries, including Vanuatu, constituted an important part of
China's foreign policy, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is willing to make concerted efforts
with the Vanuatu government to build long-term, stable, all-round
and healthy cooperative ties for the coming new century, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy said that the smooth growth of bilateral ties between
Vanuatu and China should be attributed to the consensus between
the two nations to handle bilateral ties in accordance with the
norms of international relations.
</P>
<P>
He also extended gratitude for China's precious assistance and
support for his country, saying such assistance played a
significant role in promoting the social and economic development
of the island country.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy expressed the hope that China, as a dialog partner of the
SPF, will continue to play an active role in South-Pacific affairs.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also briefed the guests on China's political, economic and
social developments.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi were among those
present at the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
