<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Timor's Ballot Voter Turnout Exceeds 95 PC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- East Timor's direct ballot voter
turnout exceeded 95 percent, director of the U.N. electoral
advisory body Corrina Perelli told reporters in Dili, capital of
East Timor, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Based on the boxes collected from 193 of 220 ballot committees
until Tuesday morning, some 432,287 East Timorese, or 98.6 percent
of eligible voters, cast their vote during Monday's direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
"We can thus say that there was a massive turnout of voters,"
Perelli was quoted by the Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
She said tens of thousands of people who had fled their homes
and villages returned to vote.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 451,000 of the 800,000 people in
East Timor were eligible to vote in the ballot.
</P>
<P>
Perelli said the ballot boxes were flown on Tuesday by U.N.
Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) helicopters from the districts to
the counting house, an old museum next to the central police
headquarters in Dili.
</P>
<P>
On the killing of Joel Lopez Gomez, a local U.N. staff member,
spokesman of the UNAMET David Wimhurst, who accompanied Perelli
during the press conference, said the victim was walking with
other U.N. staff members after the poll closed in Atsabe village,
Ermera district, when pro-integration militiamen in the area
opened fire.
</P>
<P>
"The gunfire was into the ground, and during this Gomez was
stabbed and his lungs punctured. He died an hour or two later,"
Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. team had flown to the site on Tuesday to investigate the
circumstances of the killing, he added.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that the safety of the 4,000 local U.N. staff
members is the responsibility of the Indonesian Police.
</P>
<P>
The referendum under an agreement among Indonesia, Portugal and
the United Nations was for voters to choose between special
autonomy within Indonesia and independence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in
1976, has been seen by the U.N. General Assembly as a
non-self-governing territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
