<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Exchange Drug Traffickers for Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Iran is to exchange jailed drug
traffickers for the safe return of four foreign tourists and their
Iranian guide taken hostages two weeks ago in the southeastern
province of Kerman.
</P>
<P>
Local Persian-language newspapers reported Tuesday that the
authorities have handed over two members of the Shah-Bakhsh tribe
to the police for the exchange later this week as demanded by the
abductors.
</P>
<P>
The two tribesmen are identified as Ghader Shah-Bakhsh and
Hussein Khassi-Farahani, both head of a major drug network. They
were arrested during a shoot-out with security forces in July,
which left five Shah-Bakhsh members dead.
</P>
<P>
The Shah-Bakhsh tribe is one of two major tribes near the
borders with Pakistan and Afghanistan, a region hard-hit by drug
trafficking. The tribe kidnaped four foreign tourists and their
Iranian guide on August 14 in retaliation for the police crackdown.
</P>
<P>
The four foreigners are two Spanish priests, 70-year-old
Joaquin Fernandez and 57-year-old Cosme Puerto, another Spaniard,
40-year-old Pedro Garcia, and Italian civil engineer Massimo
Cattabriga, 37. They were taken hostage from their hotel in
Kerman province.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the authorities and tribesmen have been
going on to secure their safe return. A provincial official said
the five hostages would be freed by the weekend, and their should
be no delay.
</P>
<P>
The tribe is also demanding the return of the bodies of those
killed in battle with the police, as well as a guarantee of
immunity from prosecution by the government, the papers here said.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapers and their captives have been "entirely
surrounded" by the police, but no action was taken to arrest
them, the papers added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
