<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Companies Trying to Develop Technology for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- As shopping over the Internet
gains popularity, more and more consumers want to know how the
products feel that they are thinking of buying.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet this demand, a number of Israeli high
technology companies are working on realistic tactile sensation
technology, the latest issue of Israel Business Today magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
This technology will give an Internet user the ability to feel
the texture of a pair of corduroy pants or to test drive a new
car, feeling how it takes the curves, or accelerates.
</P>
<P>
Using this technology, almost all touch sensation can be
simulated, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Companies working on realistic tactile sensation are reportedly
following up on work originally done by Stanford University and
the U.S. National Aeronautics Agency for force feedback
technology.
</P>
<P>
Israeli companies are using broadband technology and fast
Internet transmission, in a hope to achieve the super quick
date exchange rates needed to bring this new sensation
technology to market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
