<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Capability to Cope With Quake Very Limited: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli army official has
said that Israel can not cope with on its own an earthquake of the
scale that hit Turkey recently.
</P>
<P>
Local rescue teams will not be able to save all the people
trapped under buildings in case of a major earthquake in the
country, Colonel Uri Ben Yehuda of the Home Front Command of
Israeli army said.
</P>
<P>
Considering the rate that the Israeli rescue teams worked in
Turkey, which was hit by a 7.4-magnitude quake on August 17, such
teams would reportedly be able to save only about 200 people from
fallen buildings even though thousands were trapped, Haaretz daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ben Yehuda explained that rescue teams can only work in 60
buildings simultaneously, but that it is impossible to estimate
how much time will be needed to clear each building.
</P>
<P>
Ben Yehuda said that in case of a national disaster,
international assistance would be needed immediately and that
Israel would not be able to handle the situation on its own.
</P>
<P>
He added that since the Israeli army is geared to function
during wars, not natural disasters, a national concept will have
to be formulated.
</P>
<P>
"I have no doubt that a central body is needed to deal with
large-scale disasters on the national level," he said.
</P>
<P>
Military sources also told Haaretz that they has recommended
that the government conduct "earthquake exercises," similar to
those conducted in Japan and the United States, but it rejected
the notion for fear that such exercises might cause panic.
</P>
<P>
In a recent report, Haaretz quoted a earthquake researcher as
saying that there might be a strong earthquake in the Dead Sea
area within the next twenty years, and a lot of old buildings in
Jerusalem could be damaged in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Control Committee of Israeli Knesset
(parliament) has recently began a series of discussions on the
country's preparation for a strong earthquake.
</P>
<P>
And the committee is also expected to invite Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to brief the committee on the government's plan to
deal with the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
