<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 31, (Xinhua) -- Following are major news items in
leading Nigerian newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
New Nigerian:
</P>
<P>
-- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo is to launch a program
for national moral and ethnical rebirth on September 9 this year
as part of government's efforts to promote positive attitudinal
change among Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Daily Times:
</P>
<P>
-- President Obasanjo told the Nigerien Head of State Daouda
Malam Wanke on Monday, who paid a one-day working visit to the
country, to ensure that everything was done to see through his
administration's transition program which is expected to
culminate in the election of a civilian government in November.
</P>
<P>
This Day:
</P>
<P>
-- In a bid to control the excess liquidity in the country's
financial system, the Central Bank of Nigeria mopped up an
estimated 95.5 billion naira (about one billion U.S. dollars) from
circulation in the first half of 1999 through the Open Market
Operations.
</P>
<P>
The Punch:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank are
to assist Nigeria put in place a social security system, which is
aimed at protecting its most vulnerable citizens from the effects
of economic reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
