<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Decides to Grant Exporters Tax Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has decided to grant all
exporters a tax holiday as part of the efforts to increase
exports, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision adopted on Monday during a ministerial meeting
under Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri also applies to the
companies that have an independent budget for export activities,
the English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The decision was aimed at encouraging companies to work in the
export and marketing fields, Cabinet Affairs Minister Talaat Ahmed
Hammad told reporters after the ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
Economists and exporters have expressed welcome to the measure
as a much-needed boost to Egypt's weak export sector, according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
The government decision will primarily encourage manufacturers
who were concentrating on the domestic market to explore export
markets, David Shelbi, economist at brokerage house EFG-Hermes,
was quoted by the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Others have described the move as excellent, voicing confidence
that it would enlarge Egypt's export volume.
</P>
<P>
But Shelbi said the decree will unlikely have a significant
short-term impact on the government revenue, given the small size
of Egypt's exports and an array of existing tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hammad announced a decision to form a committee of
the ministers of trade, economy, public enterprise, finance and
planning, plus the Central Bank governor, to study the creation of
a central unit to monitor trade statistics.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet sources said the proposed unit is to avoid having
different trade figures released by different ministries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's exports stand at 1.015 billion U.S. dollars in the
third quarter of the 1998-99 fiscal year ending on June 30, down
from 1.028 billion dollars in the second quarter and 1.083 billion
dollars in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The total exports for the 1997-98 fiscal year were 5.13 billion
dollars, down from 5.35 billion dollars of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
