<HEADLINE> UAE, Oman to Issue Joint Visas to Boost Tourism, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) and Oman will start issuing joint visas by October to
promote tourism and trade, according to a top Omani tourism
official.
</P>
<P>
"The proposal has been approved in principle by the
authorities concerned and a mechanism is being worked out to
ensure the complete success of this unique exercise in the
region," Omani Tourism Undersecretary Mohsin Bin Khamis Al Balushi
was quoted by the Gulf News as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The issuance of joint visas is meant for tourists and business
people, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Calling the joint visa a "rare product designed to complement
and supplement each other," he said that Oman and the UAE are
bound by history and geography.
</P>
<P>
Oman-UAE ties received a further boost in May when the two
countries signed a historic border demarcation agreement. In
July, the Omani government allowed UAE nationals to own real
estates in the country.
</P>
<P>
"My dream is to see all six states of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) joining the fold for the good of the region," Al
Balushi said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the UAE and Oman, the GCC also includes Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
