<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Benefit From Turkish Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Defense Minister
Salem Al-Sabah said that his country will make good use of
Turkey's military technology to develop its warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Salem, who is also deputy prime minister, said that during his
upcoming visit to Turkey, due in late September, the Kuwaiti side
will get acquainted with the modern military technologies of
Turkey used for their F-16 fighters.
</P>
<P>
"We might use the Turkish expertise to develop part of our
military aircraft," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has several F-18 jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Turkey, Iraq's two neighbors, are harboring bases
used by U.S. and British aircraft monitoring the so-called no-fly
zones in northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed by the U.S.-led allies after the
1991 Gulf War, sparked by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, with
a claimed aim of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiites
Muslims in the south from "Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
Salem's visit to Turkey, at the invitation of Turkish Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem, who paid a two-day visit here last Tuesday,
is to be part of his four-nation tour that will also take him to
China, South Korea and Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
