<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 600 Gall-stones Taken out from Chinese Patient </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese surgeons have taken out a
total of 624 stones weighing over 200 grams from the gall of a
woman patient in northeast China's Heilongjiang province.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year old woman Yang Ming was diagnosed to have
cholecystitis and cholelithiasis by doctors of the No. 1 Attached
Hospital of the Harbin Medical University after suffering from an
upset and aching stomach for years.
</P>
<P>
When they found they could not drag the gall out of the
bellybutton as they did in normal practice because of the great
number and size of the stones in the patient's gall, the surgeons
used a special pump pipe to get rid of the bile in the gall and
then a nipper to pick out the stones.
</P>
<P>
The patient are recovering fast and is in good condition now.
</P>
