<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Tumble in Tokyo on Weak Economic Indicators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Discouraged by weak economic
indicators, Stock prices plunged in Tokyo Tuesday with the key
Nikkei index closing below 17,500 for the first time in more than
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 482.41 points, or 2.69
percent, from Monday's close to end at 17,436.56.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 40.92 points or 2.73 percent to 1,457.
02.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 709.21 million
shares from 455.44 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
Before the stock market opened Tuesday, Japan's Ministry of
International Trade and Industry said that country's industrial
production fell by a seasonally adjusted 0.6 percent in July from
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The data was worse than expected, prompting investors to sell
stocks after recent gains, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Share prices fell in most business sectors, and export-oriented
issues were hit by the yen's strength against the U.S. dollar and
an unfavorable performance on Wall Street Monday, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 861 to 337, with 100 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
