<HEADLINE> Nationalist Motive Suspected in Murder near West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police have launched
a wide-ranging investigation after two Israelis were found
murdered near the West Bank Monday, saying the possibility of a
nationalist motive behind the killing cannot not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak expressed shock Monday night
at the murder of Yehezkel Shai, 26, and his girlfriend, Sharon
Steinmetz, 21, and called on police to make every effort to catch
the perpetrators, Israel Radio said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the couple, who went on a hiking trip Sunday,
were found in the Megiddo area near the northern border of the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Northern region police chief Alik Ron told Israel Radio
that police were investigating all aspects and emphasizing the
possibility of a nationalist motive behind the killing.
</P>
<P>
Israel's security facilities have warned recently that militant
 Palestinian groups might renew their anti-Israel activity in an
attempt to derail the peace process, which the moderate
government of Barak and the Palestinians are trying to put back
on track.
</P>
<P>
Islamic groups Hamas and Islamic Jihad, which oppose
Israeli-Palestinian peacemaking, have killed scores of Israelis in
a series of terror attacks in Israel since 1993, when Israel
and the Palestinians signed the historic Oslo peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Haaretz said, however, that marks found on
the body of the murdered woman indicated that she had also
been raped. There have been no similar cases in the past
where members of Hamas or Islamic Jihad had combined acts of
rape with murders, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steady Growth of Urbanization in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year marks
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China. Over the past five decades, China's achievements in all
economic sectors have attracted worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua News Agency is to release about 20 stories about the
nation's economy. The first of the series was released on August
17. This is the eleventh.
</P>
<P>
Urbanization has been expanding rapidly in China over the past
50 years since the founding of the People's Republic in 1949, with
the number of cities rising from 132 in 1949 to 668 at present,
according to the Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of cities with a population of
more than 500,000 each increased from 12 to 81 in the past five
decades. And the country's urban population now accounts for 30
percent of the nation's total, up from 12 percent 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Ministry of Construction said that small cities
with a population of less than 200,000 each developed most rapidly
over the past 20 years, signaling a boom in the rural economic
development which has ushered in the urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that the reform and opening-up policy adopted
at the end of 1978 has greatly stimulated rural economic
development, particularly in the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country's urbanization development strategy has
paid off by controlling the development of large cities and giving
rational development to small and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
Ministry sources also said that the area of Chinese cities has
been expanding over the past 50 years, and now accounts for 18
percent of the country's total land area, as against 7.6 percent
in 1984. The suburban counties around major cities such as Beijing,
Shanghai, Tianjin, Harbin, Wuhan, Nanjing, and Guangzhou, as well
as other cities, have developed into satellite cities and towns
over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, city groups centering on very large metropolises
have come into being in recent years, including those in the delta
areas of the Yangtze River, the Pearl River, and the Bohai Rim
areas.
</P>
<P>
However, uneven economic development has resulted in an uneven
distribution of cities between eastern and western China.
</P>
<P>
To speed up urbanization in western China, the government has
taken a series of encouraging policies to support the development
of large cities in this region in a bid to bring about development
of the surrounding small and medium-size cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 06:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Shuts Down Hamas Office, 12 Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordan shut down the Amman office
of the Palestinian Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) in a
surprise move Monday, arrested 12 of its members and put four
senior Hamas leaders on its wanted list.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown was carried out because the Hamas office,
registered as a business office in Amman, and its members "had
been involved in activities incompatible with their licenses," the
semiofficial Jordan Times quoted officials from the interior
ministry as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Police rounded up 12 Hamas activists and issued arrest warrants
to four Hamas leaders who are currently outside Amman on a visit
to Iran, the Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
The warrants were issued against Hamas spokesman Ibrahim
Ghosheh, former poliburo chief Musa Abu Marzouk, current leader
of the movement`s poliburo khaled Misha`al and Hamas
representative in Jordan Mohammad Nazzal.
</P>
<P>
In a separate move on Monday, the Jordanian police also shut
down the Amman bureau of the "Palestinian Al Muslemah," a Hamas
-affiliated organization.
</P>
<P>
It's not immediately clear whether the Jordanian authorities
had consulted with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who is also a
close personal friend of Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein,
before the shutdown and the arrest.
</P>
<P>
Hamas is known as a militant Palestinian organization which
opposes making peace with Israel but stands for a "holy war" to
liberate all Palestinian territories and establish an Islamic
state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is a staunch supporter of the Palestinians but called
for an early resumption of peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians as well as Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming the
second Arab country after Egypt to strike a peace treaty with the
Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
