<HEADLINE> UAE Sends Ambulances to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen ambulances donated by
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) to the people of Bosnia could
reach them by mid-September, the Gulf News daily reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ambulances, which cost 500,000 U.S. dollars, will be the
first ambulances that some Bosnian cities will have had since the
end of the Bosnian war in 1995, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to Nasr Ishak, senior liaison officer in Abu Dhabi
for the United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR), the
UNHCR will possibly hand over the ambulances to Sarajevo on
September 18.
</P>
<P>
But the final decision has to be made after further
consultation between the parties concerned, namely the Zayed
Foundation, which donated the ambulances, the Bosnian government
and the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
"The 15 ambulances have been built to specifications for
the Bosnian situation," the UNHCR official said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Zayed Foundation's donation of the
ambulances to Bosnia has set the stage for further cooperation
between the UAE and the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
The foundation has been invited to take part in the
UNHCR-organized non-government organization conference in Geneva in
October, he said. 
</P>
