<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Govt to Impose 30 Pc Duty on Imported Ceramics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
agreed to impose 30 percent duty on imported ceramics products,
press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This agreement was reached recently after a series of meetings
between the Bangladesh Ceramic Wares Manufacturers' Association
(BCWMA) and the National Board of Revenue and other government
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Low-quality and cheap-rated foreign ceramic products are now
flooding the local market posing a serious threat to the country's
export-earning ceramics producers, the BCWMA alleged.
</P>
<P>
The ceramic industry is a fledging one in this South Asian
country, and as a non-traditional item, ceramic at this moment is
a major exportable item having a high degree of value addition.
</P>
<P>
The earnings from different types of table-ware, kitchenware of
porcelain or china and articles other than porcelain exports stood
at 2.5 billion taka (about 550.5 million U.S. dollars) in the
1998-99 fiscal year ending on June 30. 
