<HEADLINE> Brushfires Plague Southern California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Firefighters Monday battled
brushfires all over southern California that have scorched
thousands of acres, forced evacuations, damaged buildings and
posed a threat to power lines.
</P>
<P>
Officials said efforts to extinguish the fires were hampered by
strong, erratic winds, steep terrains, and a recent heat wave that
sent temperatures soaring to 100 Fahrenheit degrees.
</P>
<P>
One blaze, near Lake Arrowhead, about 75 miles east of Los
Angeles, has consumed 17,000 acres of brush and forest in an area
called Apply Valley.
</P>
<P>
About 400 residents, hikers, campers and vacationers were
evacuated over the weekend. Thirty structures were burned.
</P>
<P>
Together, the fires have burned more than 51,000 acres Monday
in southern California, according to California Department of
Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Wind-driven wildfires Monday also burned more than 50,000 acres
of timber, dry brush and cactus in other five western states of
Idaho, Montana, Nevada, Utah and Washington.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the National Fire Information Center in Boise,
Idaho, said the chain of blazes across the western U.S. states
over the past week had pushed the total amount of land burned this
year to more than four million acres -- almost double the annual
average for the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Janelle Smith, a center spokeswoman, said that two years of
weather disruptions caused by the El Nino and La Nina phenomena
were partially to blame, with dry summers leaving much of the
south and east unusually fire-prone and damp winters in the
northwest leaving forests and hillsides thick with the scrubby
growth that fuels forest fires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
