<HEADLINE> Japan's Jobless Rate Remains at a Record High in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Japan's unemployment rate stayed
at a record high 4.9 percent for the second straight month in July,
with female joblessness worsening slightly, the Management and
Coordination Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
From last year to July, the number of unemployed rose by 490,
000 to 3.19 million, and the number of employed dropped by 800,000
to 64.97 million for the 18th consecutive month of decline, the
agency added.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally-adjusted jobless rate for women rose by 0.2
percentage to 4.6 percent in July, while that for men remained at
a record high of 5.1 percent, a preliminary report by the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
An agency official said some bright aspects of employment are
emerging, but an immediate improvement is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
Another report by Japan's Labor Ministry said the ratio of job
offers to job seekers was 0.46 in July, the same as in the
previous month, meaning there were 46 job offers for every 100 job
seekers.
</P>
<P>
Compared with last year, job offers rose in sectors such as
construction, telecommunications, transport, service and real
estate, but dropped in the manufacturing sector, the ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
