<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Encephalitis Toll Hits 150 in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 31 (Xinhua) -- At least 150 people have died
from the Japanese Encephalitis (JE) throughout Nepal so far since
the onset of monsoon season, The Kathmandu Post quoted the
Department of Health Services as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The highly affected areas are the Terai plain in south-western
Nepal, with 98 deaths reported from the region. Kathmandu does not
have any reported cases so far.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Encephalitis, a vector borne disease, emerges with the
onset of warm rainy season and flares up throughout monsoon. JE
virus is carried by mosquito that is infected from biting pigs.
Pigeons, ducks and horses can also serve as host to JE virus. The
early symptoms are fever, headache, nausea and vomiting which may
end up as paralysis in later stages.
</P>
<P>
According to epidemiological analysis prepared by the World
Health Organization in Nepal in 1998, more than 11.5 million
people are at constant risk of JE in Nepal. The most affected
areas are primarily the southern plains that are inhabited by the
Tharu community since they raise pigs.
</P>
<P>
The early action that can be taken to prevent the disease is
vaccination. There are no effective treatment after the disease
strikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
