<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Implement Master Plan to Reduce Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to implement a
10-year master plan to reduce its poverty rate by uplifting the
living standard of its rural population, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for the master plan, a countrywide survey had been
conducted to gather data on industries and the availability of
resources such as raw materials, agro-resources, minerals and
manpower, said a spokesman for the Ministry of Vocational Training
and Rural Industries.
</P>
<P>
The plan, funded by the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP), will be implemented by the Ministry of Vocational Training
and Rural Industries under the auspices of the International Labor
Organization.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman did not specify how much money will be
needed to implement the plan.
</P>
<P>
According to a UNDP report on Sri Lanka, the poverty rate in
the country was 18 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
But Sri Lanka's Department of Census and Statistics said in a
recent report that about 40 percent of the country's population
live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
The report said nearly half of Sri Lanka's population of 18.5
million live without access to electricity. In some districts, 80
percent of the population have no access to electricity.
</P>
<P>
Access to safe drinking water is out of reach for over a
quarter of the population, leading to the rapid spread of
diarrhea, cholera and other diseases, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
