<DOCNO> XIE19990831.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Rate Rises to 5.7 Percent in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in
Thailand rose to 5.7 percent at the end of May this year, and one
in every 12 workers lost jobs or could not find work during the
past three months, the Bangkok Post reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a government report as saying that the
unemployment rate in Thailand has now tripled since the end of
1996, as two years of recession, a real estate market slump and
cost-cutting by companies have left 1.87 million people out of
work.
</P>
<P>
The inability of new high-school and college graduates to find
work swelled the jobless queues, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda was quoted as
saying that though absolute unemployment in Thailand had risen,
the pace of the increase had slowed considerably.
</P>
<P>
He said two government spending packages in the past five
months have helped some people find jobs.
</P>
<P>
There had been an improvement among commercial service
providers and small businesses, he said, acknowledging that
construction workers had been severely affected.
</P>
<P>
The workforce of Thailand as of May 31 this year was 33.08
million, or 54 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government announced a 1.5-billion-U.S.-dollar program
in March to create about 500,000 jobs, mostly for unskilled
laborers to build public works.
</P>
<P>
The government report said the program should help reduce the
jobless rate to 4.2 percent by the year's end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
