<HEADLINE> Venezuela Tightens Security Around Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's authorities
tightened security outside Congress to prevent more violence
between supporters and opponents of President Hugo Chavez.
</P>
<P>
The measure was taken after scores of Chavez's supporters and
opponents clashed outside Congress where the Constitutional
National Assembly (ANC) is scheduled to examine a possible
modification of the decree of legislative emergency. Thirty people
were injured in the clash.
</P>
<P>
The clash happened when supporters of Chavez and security
forces stopped opposition legislators from jumping the gate of the
legislative headquarters to meet their supporters.
</P>
<P>
Under the order, police force and the National Guard were
posted outside the Congress building, where the pros and cons of
Chavez shouted rival slogans. The ANC is elected through a
nationwide poll under a decree of Chavez to spearhead the country'
s economic and political reforms.
</P>
<P>
ANC President Luis Maquileana, a supporter of Chavez, warned
against a repeating of the violence, which he said was instigated
by the opposition. 
</P>
