<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poorest Villages in Northwest China Now Well-off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A total of 52 villages in the
Guyuan region of northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region,
formerly known as the poorest area in China, have achieved the
goal of leading a well-to-do life.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the local government has succeeded in lifting many
villages out of poverty and has continued to help them improve
their lives.
</P>
<P>
It began by choosing some villages with comparatively better
natural conditions and economic foundations as experimental units
to develop their economy.
</P>
<P>
Within seven years, the number of such villages has increased
to 180, with a population of 320,000.
</P>
<P>
Now, the per capita net income of these experimental villages
has risen from 455 yuan to 2,235 yuan a year, and 52 of them are
now considered the well-to-do.
</P>
<P>
For the past seven years, the local government has helped these
villages make the best use of their advantages in geographic
location and resources.
</P>
<P>
For instance, Shanmin village in Xijie County has encouraged
every family to enter the business of cattle and sheep butchering
and transporting.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the village now earns more than 6.6 million yuan a
year, and the net income per family exceeds 10,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Libao village in Haiyuan County has made great efforts to
develop forestry by using Yellow River water, and its per capita
net income last year reached 3,950 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
