<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Officials, International Observers Praise E. Timor Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian officials and
international observers praised the largely peaceful direct ballot
held in East Timor on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Over 90 percent of the 451,000 registered voters turned out at
polling booths, with the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET)
calling the day "very successful."
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Post said Tuesday that tension and isolated
incidents marked some areas, including seven polling stations that
had to suspend operations due to security concerns.
</P>
<P>
A local staff member of UNAMET was stabbed to death outside a
polling booth in Atsabe, Ermera, late Monday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special emissary for East
Timor Jamsheed Marker expressed satisfaction with the conduct of
the direct ballot, saying it had proceeded in a "fair, free and
secret" manner.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in Dili, capital of East Timor, that Annan
had extended warm congratulations to the East Timorese on the
smooth conduct of the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, Indonesian Minister of Foreign Affairs Ali Alatas
said he was filled with "hopeful anticipation."
</P>
<P>
However, he added that it was too soon to say he was
"relieved."
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the government's position was to encourage the East
Timorese to remain part of Indonesia, but he reiterated the
government's commitment to abiding by the results of the vote.
</P>
<P>
"After personally spending so much time on efforts to find a
comprehensive and just solution to the East Timor question, of
course I'm very happy that finally the opportunity has arrived for
such a solution," The Jakarta Post quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Military Commander Gen. Wiranto praised the UNAMET
for peacefully conducting the ballot.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen smooth balloting at hundreds of polling centers
and only a minor incident that happened away from the stations,"
he said after attending a meeting of the Council for the Upholding
of Security and Law here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesian Army Chief of Staff General Subagyo
Hadisiswoyo said the headquarters of East Timor's military command
would be moved to Ende in Flores Island following the ballot.
</P>
<P>
"The army military units concerned are making the necessary
preparations for the command headquarters' move to Ende in Flores
Island," he said, adding that the East Timor command's
headquarters would be moved regardless of the results of the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET chief electoral officer Jeff Fischer said the vote count
will start after all ballot boxes arrive in Dili Tuesday
afternoon. It will take UNAMET a week to finish the count.
</P>
<P>
The ballot count would be a transparent affair and
representatives of observers and both factions would be allowed to
witness the process, he added.
</P>
<P>
The August 30 ballot will allow the East Timorese to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
