<HEADLINE> Beijing Vows to Open More Sectors to Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital has vowed to
open up more sectors to overseas investment and adopt more
diversified means to utilize such investment.
</P>
<P>
A leading foreign trade official in Beijing said the city has
many advantages for overseas investors. A number of Sino-overseas
shopping malls are now open, and Sino-overseas trade companies and
travel agencies are also being planned in the city.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to open sectors such as banking, insurance,
commerce, transportation, telecommunications, foreign trade and
tourism to overseas investment in order to qualify for entry into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The official added that Beijing aims to achieve significant
breakthroughs in introducing overseas investment into the city's
infrastructure, renovation of old buildings, the Zhongguancun
Technological Zone, and other important industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
In addition to attracting direct overseas investment, Beijing
is also seeking to list successful enterprises on domestic and
overseas stock markets and encourage overseas investors to merge
or acquire enterprises in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
To lure more overseas investment, Beijing will sponsor two
symposiums during the second half of this year on economic
cooperation between Beijing and Hong Kong, and between Beijing and
Taiwan. Along with participating in trade talks and organizing
promotion groups overseas, the city also plans to create an
Internet website to better publicize municipal information.
</P>
<P>
Beijing approved another 309 overseas-funded enterprises during
the first half this year, attracting 986 million US dollars in
overseas investment. This year, the city used 1.37 billion US
dollars in overseas investment during the first half, an increase
of 3.7 percent over the same six-month period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
