<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholar Finds Ancient Book Road Leading to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Along with the famous Silk Road
connecting the East with the West, there apparently was also a
Book Road between China and Japan in ancient times, a Chinese
scholar announced here recently.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Wang Yong, director of the Research Institute of Japanese
Culture at Zhejiang University, said the Book Road played a major
role in spreading Chinese culture to Japan and other neighboring
countries during the Tang Dynasty (618 - 907 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, who has been to Japan many times to research
the subject, the Book Road consisted of two routes, with one
extending from Chang'an (the present-day Xi'an), then the capital
of China, to Japan through the Korean Peninsula, and the other
running from the lower reaches of the Yangtze River, China's
longest river, directly to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Those engaged in the exchange of books were mainly diplomatic
envoys, monks, and merchants, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Chinese books were carried by sea to Japan
during this period, according to Wang, and a Japanese monk named
Ruxuan alone took more than 5,000 volumes of Chinese classics back
to Japan after studying in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese-language books were also brought to China from other
Asian countries through these channels, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the silk taken to the West over the Silk Road, many of
the books exchanged via the Book Road still exist, and are playing
a role in promoting cultural progress, Wang added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
