<HEADLINE> Spirlea Upsets Coetzer on First Day of U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Irina Spirlea of Romania
pulled off the first major upset of the $14.5 million U.S. Open
Tennis Championship today as she knocked off sixth seed Amanda
Coetzer of South Africa 6-1, 7-5 in New York.
</P>
<P>
Spirlea, a semifinalist at the Open in 1997, wasted three match
points at 5-3 and Coetzer rallied to even the second set at 5-5.
But Spirlea broke again to go up 6-5 and served out the match.
</P>
<P>
Former champions Martina Hingis and Andre Agassi are joined by
top contenders Venus Williams and Yevgeny Kafelnikov as the
headliners on today's opening day of play.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, the 1997 champion and last year's runner-up, takes on
Kveta Hrdlickova of the Czech Republic to open the evening session.
Fresh off winning her fifth title of the year, the third-seeded
Williams goes against qualifier Tatiana Poutchek of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, the second seed and 1994 winner, plays Sweden's Nicklas
Kulti in the second evening match. Kafelnikov, seeded third, faces
Spain's Alberto Martin in a day match.
</P>
<P>
Five other seeds play their opening-round matches on the women'
s side. Eighth seed Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic, a
semifinalist last year, plays Shi-Ting Wang of Chinese Taipei; and
10th seed and 1994 champion Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain beat
16-year-old Wimbledon quarterfinalist Jelena Dokic of Australia 7-
5, 6-1. Dokic committed 45 unforced errors and was broken six
times in the swirling wind.
</P>
<P>
Also, No. 12 Barbara Schett of Austria battles American
qualifier Tracy Singian; No. 13 Dominique Van Roost of Belgium
faces Canada's Maureen Drake; and Australian Open finalist Amelie
Mauresmo of France, the 15th seed, meets Justine Henin of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
For the men, eighth seed and 1998 semifinalist Carlos Moya of
Spain takes on French Open semifinalist Dominik Hrbaty of Slovakia;
10th seed Marcelo Rios of Chile goes against Martin Damm of the
Czech Republic; and No. 12 Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands
routed national junior champion Philip King of the Unites States 6-
1, 6-4, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, Sampras and two-time defending men's champion
Patrick Rafter of Australia will play their opening-round matches
over the next two days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
