<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Dong Ethnic Group Shows Zeal for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Despite being a poverty stricken
county where agricultural workers only have a per capita annual
income of 1,200 yuan (about 144 US dollars), the Dong minority
people of Tianzhu are keen to stress the importance of education.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the county's annual fiscal income has been
allocated for building and repairing schools in recent years,
according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
"All dilapidated houses in middle and primary schools in
Tianzhu have been repaired and upgraded," said Yao Xueyin, an
official in charge of the region's news publicity, who added that
the number of schools has risen from 116 in 1949, when new China
was founded, to the current 347, and the number of students from
about 15,000 to more than 70,000.
</P>
<P>
According to Yao, few Dong people were good at basic skills
several decades ago, but since 1949 more than 16,700 college
graduates and young people with special expertise have grown up in
Tianzhu, where more than 1.1 million Dong people now reside,
accounting for nearly 40 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, the chances to receive a college education
are still very poor for Chinese young people, especially in
minority areas, but frequently in Tianzhu, in southwest China's
Guizhou Province, one family boasts several college graduates in
its ranks. And the small village of Zhangzhai in the town of
Gaoniang reports that it has more than 100 college graduates.
</P>
<P>
"Government officials in Taizhu share a common understanding
that an ethnic group such as the Dong can only have hope for the
future by putting the emphasis on the development of education,"
Yao said.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the county have sold the two limousines awarded
by the provincial government for their outstanding achievements in
alleviating poverty: using the money to build a primary school.
They now take buses for business trips.
</P>
<P>
Another example of the dedication is provided by Yang Kaibo
whose parents even left their home town to find higher paid work
in a bid to earn more money to pay for his college tuition.
</P>
<P>
Yang enrolled in Xi'an Electronic Industry University last year
and his family have also sold all their household appliances to
pay for his studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
