<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Berlin supports Poland to get the European Union (EU)
membership "as quickly as possible", said German Foreign Minister
Joschka Fischer Monday at the annual meeting with his Polish and
French counterpart, Bronislaw Geremek and Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
"Ten years after the end of Cold War there is the question,
when the EU can also overstep the former border between the two
blocks," Fischer said. "In my personal view, Poland is already a
EU member," he added, underlining the fact that Poland had been
accepted as a NATO member and its economy had been closely
integrated with Germany and the EU. (Germany-Poland-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Monday called a referendum
on the future of East Timor a success.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters that all
reports -- official and unofficial -- "indicate that the U.N.-
administered vote in East Timor was a success, with approximately
90 percent of those registered casting ballots." Referring to the
next phases of the process -- counting the vote and transition to
either independence or autonomy within Indonesia -- Foley said: "
Indonesia maintains the responsibility for maintaining order and
we remain concerned about the potential for violence." (US-E.Timor-
Referendum)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi Zuetir Monday asked
the U.S. State of Secretary Madeleine Albright to pressure Israel
to end its daily aggression on the country.
</P>
<P>
Zuetir told the independent Central News Agency that Israel
usually escalates the situation in south Lebanon ahead of any
international envoy's visit to the region for reactivation of the
peace process. (Lebanon-Israel-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak abandoned an
ultimatum to the Palestinians Monday, saying he expected answers
from Palestinian leaders within three days to his proposed
modification of a U.S.-brokered peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a parliamentary committee of foreign and defense
affairs, Barak said it would be known within three days whether
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat would agree
to Israeli proposals on the implementation of the Wye agreement. "
The prospects (for an agreement), I believe, are more than 50-50,"
Barak told reporters after the briefing. (Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
</TEXT>
