<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over One Million Londoners Rush to Carnival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The streets of west London were
transformed into rivers of color on Monday as over one million
people rushed to Notting Hill for Europe's largest carnival.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 costumed bands and floats made their way through the
three-mile route which has been turned into part of the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Bone-shaking bass lines pumping from dozens of sound systems
were pitched against shrills from thousands of whistles during
this multi-cultural festival.
</P>
<P>
Some 7,000 officers were on duty, but police said they had seen
little trouble, with only two arrests by late afternoon, one for
drunkenness and the other for a drugs offense.
</P>
<P>
A record 400,000 people turned out for children's carnival on
Sunday, also with relatively few problems.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the carnival's organizers said: "It's been a
fantastic atmosphere here, the crowds have been up, it's been a
really peaceful carnival, everyone's enjoying themselves."
</P>
<P>
And a police spokesman said:"It is busy but everyone is
enjoying themselves and it is quiet."
</P>
<P>
The Notting Hill Carnival has its roots in a 1964 street
procession aimed at bringing together an Afro-Caribbean community
blighted by racism and prejudice.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Notting Hill carnival has grown steadily
and reflected the multi-cultural nature of British society, with
performers from all over the country as well as countries ranging
from Afghanistan, Bulgaria and Russia to the Caribbean, South
America and Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
