<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Protestant Militia to Hand in More Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's pro-British
Loyalist Volunteer Force (LVF) said on Monday that it would soon
give in more arms to authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Protestant LVF, the only Northern Ireland guerrilla group
to have handed in weapons from the province's conflict, also
called on its main Roman Catholic rival, the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), to follow suit and give up arms.
</P>
<P>
The LVF said in a statement its "ruling army council" had
"decided to go ahead with the second phase of our arms
decommissioning (which) commenced on December 18, 1998".
</P>
<P>
On that date, about 10 guns as well as a batch of ammunition,
grenades and other materials were given to the province's
independent disarmament commission.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that the IRA and its fellow travellers immediately
commence a reciprocative act of decommissioning," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The LVF opposed last year's landmark Good Friday peace deal
which was signed by the IRA's political ally Sinn Fein and the
political allies of pro-British guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
But after referendums in Northern Ireland and the Irish
Republic overwhelmingly approved the Good Friday deal, the LVF
announced it was calling off hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Its handover of weapons last year was hailed by Britain as a
significant step.
</P>
<P>
Other pro-British guerrilla groups and the IRA have steadfastly
refused to bow to entreaties by Britain and the Irish Republic to
disarm -- a move which London and Dublin say would revive the
stalled Good Friday accord.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
